ðŸ“° *ZN5*: BCCI invites bid for IPL title sponsorship  The BCCI has invited applications from parties to bid for the title sponsorship of the Indian Premier League(IPL). The rights would be for the period between August 1st 2017 to July 2022.  Chinese mobile firm Vivo had the rights for a 2-year-period, at a cost of Rs 100 crore/yr. The firm that wins the next bid will be the title sponsors for the next 5 seasons. ðŸ“° *ZN4*: Bat Sensors, Drone Set To Enhance Tournament  England batsmen Jason Roy, Alex Hales and Ben Stokes will be among the players to use new bat sensors during the ICC Champions Trophy 2017, starting June 1.  The censors will be placed on top of the bat handle, and will provide a player's bat speed and angle of back lift.  The main aim of bringing in the technology into the tournament is to both provide more information to television audiences and, longer term, develop a coaching aid.  A drone equipped with infrared cameras will be used for advanced pitch analysis. Images captured by the drone will offer rich visual data on pitch conditions such as grass cover, grass health, and topology. CTðŸ†: England Brush AsideðŸ‘Š BangladeshðŸ‡§ðŸ‡© in the Opener  By SuperTrampðŸ€  England justifiedðŸ‘ their favourites tag with a professionalðŸ˜Ž batting performance in their opening game against Bangladesh. By chasing down 306 with 8 wickets & 16 balls to spare, England now hold the record for the highest run chase in the Champions Trophy.  The TigersðŸ¯ were put into bat on a flat track and riding on a patient tonðŸ’¯ from ðŸ’ªTamim & a handy half-century from Mushfiqur, they pushed past the 300-run mark. Liam Plunkettâš¡ was the pick of the English bowlers, finishing with figures of 4-59. Chris Woakes had to leave the field after bowling only 2 overs, due to a side strain.  Jason Roy's early dismissal in the chase roused the Bangladeshi supportðŸ‘. They had very little to cheer after that thoughðŸ˜Ÿ. Joe Rootâ­ & Alex Hales put the Three Lions on track with a superb partnershipðŸ™Œ of 159 runs. Hales fell 5 short of a deserved centuryðŸ˜ž when he holed to deep square leg. ðŸ“° *DU4*: ICC Champions Trophy: Indians "unhappy" with Edgbaston practice facility ahead of India-Pakistan clash  The Indian cricket team were unhappy with practice facilities at the Edgbaston Cricket Ground and both coach Anil Kumble and skipper Virat Kohli expressed their displeasure with the local authorities on Thursday.      It was India's first training day in Birmingham ground and they were allocated the practice arena adjacent to main stadium.      However both Kohli and Kumble had reservations as the arena was small in size. The main issue was the run-up for fast bowlers.   It was learnt that the likes of Umesh Yadav, Mohammed Shami and Hardik Pandya, all of whom have a 30-yard run-up, couldn't bowl full tilt at the nets as the distance wasn't big enough.  These days, it seems like Kohli is just a hard man to please when it comes to coaching. ðŸ“° *GT3*: Afridi Heaps Praise On Kohli, Terms India Favorites To Beat Pakistan  Former Pakistan cricket captain Shahid Afridi believes Virat Kohli's men hold an edge against his country ahead of the mega clash in the Champions Trophy on Sunday. Afridi feels recent history and the depth of India's squad are two factors that favor the defending champions against Sarfraz Ahmed's team.  "Recent history and the depth of the India squad gives India a slight edge heading into the game," Afridi wrote in his column for ICC.   The 37-year-old also praised Indian captain Virat Kohli and pacer Jasprit Bumrah.      "Kohli's credentials as a top-order batsman are known to all and he has played some memorable innings in the ODI format. For me, bowling to Kohli was always a challenge and Pakistani bowlers would have to be on top of their game against him."  "Bumrah bowls what I call the 'Pakistani Yorker' almost at will. He reminds us of our pacers of yore who had mastered the skill of bowling the perfect yorker, especially during the 90s," added Afridi. Yuvraj Singh dedicates his innings to Cancer survivors  Indian batsman Yuvraj Singh has dedicated his 'game-changing' innings to Cancer survivors on the occasion of 'Cancer Survivor Day'.  He has also expressed his thoughts and prayers to all those impacted in the London terror attack.  "My innings on #CancerSurvivorDay is dedicated to all the heroes & survivors. Also my thoughts & Prayers to all impacted in #londonattack," Yuvraj Singh tweeted. ICC approves changes to run-out, bat dimension, sending-off laws  Following its annual meeting late in May, the International Cricket Council has recommended the adoption of a number of changes to be made to the Laws of cricket.  According to the recommendations, there will be restrictions in place on bat dimensions, changes will be made to the run-out rule and umpires will be empowered to send players off the field in case of serious incidents of misconduct.  With the new recommendations in place, the bat dimensions (the thickness of edges and depth of bat) will be - an edge limit of 40mm and bat depth of 67mm (60mm for the depth plus an allowance of 7mm for a possible curve on the face of the bat).  To read full article: https://goo.gl/AeeFLa  To follow Cricket on Duta: Add to your group: +919789858563  Type ðŸ‘NS4 to like this  Type 'stop' to stop
Roston Chase earns maiden ODI call-up  Allrounder Roston Chase has been rewarded for his consistent run in the Pakistan Tests with a maiden call-up to West Indies' ODI squad for the three-match series against Afghanistan.  Twelve of the 14 members who were part of the squad for the third ODI against Pakistan - West Indies' last ODI assignment - were retained. Chadwick Walton, the wicketkeeper who made just 36 runs in three outings in that series, and left-arm spinner Veersammy Permaul were left out.  Squad: Jason Holder (captain), Devendra Bishoo, Jonathan Carter, Roston Chase, Miguel Cummins, Shannon Gabriel, Shai Hope, Alzarri Joseph, Evin Lewis, Jason Mohammed, Ashley Nurse, Kieran Powell, Rovman Poweller  To read full article: https://goo.gl/AeeFLa  To follow Cricket on Duta: Add to your group: +917550082791  Type ðŸ‘NS5 to like this  Type 'stop' to stop

BANðŸ†šNZ : Shakibâ­ & MahmudullahðŸ’¯ Script Stunning WinðŸŽ‰  By SuperTrampðŸ€  Bangladesh needed to beat New Zealand in their final league game to give themselves a chance of qualifying for the semifinals. And beat them they did. Excellent on the field as well as with the bat, the Asian Tigers registered their first ever win over the Kiwis in convincing fashion.  New Zealand opted to bat and other than Kane Williamson(57) & Ross Taylor(63) none of the other batsmen made noteworthy contributions. They lost their way in the final stages of the innings, scoring only 62 runs off the last 10 overs. They ended up posting a below par total 265/8.     Bangladesh were rocked early, losing their in-form opener Tamim Iqbal for a duck. Tim Southee was hitting the right lengths and soon dismissed two other top order batsmen to have the opposition reeling at 12/3 at the end of the 5th over. When Adam Milne castled Mushifiqur Rahim a few overs later, Bangladesh were staring down the barrel. What followed next was some unbelievable batting from the exprienced pair of Shakib & Mahmudullah. They steadied the innings by stealing singles in the middle overs and then stepped up the scoring rate. It was measured ODI batting and the duo wrested control of the game. With the game slipping from their grasp, Williamson tried to cut down the singles by bringing more fielders into the ring. This played into the hands of the Bangladeshis who were more than happy to loft over the infield. Shakib was bowled by Boult with a few runs still to get, shortly after he had reached his hundred. Mahmudllah remained unbeaten on 102 and soaked in the adulation after sealing the win.  After this terrific win, Bangladesh would be hoping that hosts England beat Australia in their match tomorrow. CTðŸ†: Terrific EnglandðŸ’ª Sends Aussies PackingðŸ’¥  ðŸ”° Australia 277/9 (50) (Head 71*, Finch 68, Wood 4/33) lost to England 240/4 (40.2 ov) (Stokes 102*, Morgan 87, Hazlewood 2/50) by 40 runs (D/L method)  A sensational ton by Ben Stokes (102*) saw England cruise past Australia by 40 runs in a Group A Champions Trophy encounter and qualify for the semifinals. More importantly, Australia have been eliminated and Bangladesh will join the hosts in the last four.  England won the toss and elected to put Australia in to bat at Edgbaston. Warner and Finch stitched together a solid 40 run partnership until the former fell. Finch and Smith then joined hands to accelerate the scoring in a partnership worth 90. After the two fell, Head played a masterful innings of 71* with the tail with wickets falling around him, to take Australia to a defendable 277-9. The wreckers in chief for England were fast bowlers Wood and Rashid who shared 8 wickets between them.  England got off to a disastrous start, losing both openers by the second over and Root soon after, leaving the tottering at a precarious 35-3. Skipper Morgan and star all-rounder Stokes then came together to tear apart the Aussie bowling with an authoritarian batting display where the former got 87 before getting run out and the later managed to end unbeaten on his century. When England were 38 runs shy of their target, the heavens opened up and the match was called off due to rain, with England winning by 40 runs according to the D/L method.  â­MoM: Ben Stokes  To follow Cricket on Duta: Add to your group: +919043013066  Type ðŸ‘FW6 to like this

All-rounder Thisara Perera takes blow to head  Sri Lanka all-rounder Thisara Perera was hit by a ball on the head during practice at Cardiff yesterday (10) ahead of the all important CT17 game against Pakistan tomorrow (12).  In a most fortunate turn of events, there has been no serious injury and although under careful observation there is currently no complaint related to head injury, with only reports of tenderness in the area of impact.  Sri Lanka Cricket will continue to keep him under strict medical observation. INDðŸ†šRSA: IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ Bowl First in 'Do-or-Die' Game  By Shadowfax:racehorse;  It's a big game in Group B as India and South Africa clash in what is a 'do-or-die' game for both teams, with the winner advancing to the semifinals.   These are two teams with very strong batting lineups and good bowling attacks. However, South Africa have not really delivered in the tournament so far, falling to a surprise defeat against Pakistan in the previous game while India's bowling let them down against Sri Lanka. Both teams have another worry in the form of their captains. Virat Kohli and AB de Villiers have not really sparkled so far and both teams will want them to fire today.   India have brought Ravichandran Ashwin back into the lineup instead of Umesh Yadav while SA have brought in Andile Phehlukwayo for Wayne Parnell. This should make for an interesting clash.   Virat Kohli has opted to bowl first today on the assumption that the wicket will remain the batting beauty it is. The weather is currently sunny and not much showers are expected today. CTðŸ†: 'Near Perfect' IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ Pummel SA OutðŸ’¥  By ShadowfaxðŸŽ  After a surprising defeat to Sri Lanka earlier, there were doubts over India's bowling attack before the 'do-or-die' clash against South Africa today and India responded by bringing in R Ashwin. And it was the bowling atack who set up India's crushing 8-wicket win over South Africa that has virtually assured them of a clash against Bangladesh in the semifinal.  After winning the toss, India opted to bowl first. Bhuvneshwar and Bumrah were tight and on target as de Kock and Amla failed to accelerate. The pressure eventually told as Amla was caught behind off Ashwin before de Kock's attempted slog off Jadeja cost him his off stump. ABD and du Plessis attempted to spur AS forward. However, two runouts changed the complexion of the game completely. ABD and Miller were the unlucky ones and SA just folded up meekly for 191 after that as Indian bowlers showed tremendous discipline and control.  The chase was always likely to be a walk in the park and that is exactly how it panned out, despite Rohit falling early. Shikhar and Virat Kohli were circumspect at first before unfurling their shots. Dhawan's haste cost him a hundred but not before he became the highest run-scorer in the tournament. Yuvraj finished the game off with a six to underline the emphatic nature of India's win.  â­MoM: Jasprit Bumrah  ðŸ“œScorecard: hq0  To follow Cricket on Duta: Add to your group: +919043015997  Type ðŸ‘HQ3 to like this 


Vijay MallyaðŸ» Booed During India ðŸ†š South Africa MatchðŸ  Fugitive businessman Vijay Mallya was on Sunday heckled by cricket fans who chanted "chor, chor" (thief, thief) as he arrived to watch the India vs South Africa Champions Trophy match at The Oval cricket ground here.  The 61-year-old chief of the now-defunct Kingfisher Airlines, who has been living in self-imposed exile in Britain since last year and is facing extradition proceedings in UK courts, walked speedily past Indian fans outside the stadium.  The former UB group chief fled the country last year and has unpaid debts close to the tune of Rs 9,000 crore taken as loans from various Indian banks.  Last week, Mallya had caused a stir by his attendance at the India vs Pakistan match in Birmingham after which he had said on Twitter that he would be attending all India matches in the ongoing ICC Champions Trophy. ðŸ“° *IK6*: Captains SpeakðŸ—£ INDðŸ†šRSA  AB de Villiers affirmed his love for captaining the South Africa team and said he would like to continue as skipper till the 2019 World Cup, despite another failure for the Proteas in an ICC tournament.  "Because I'm a good captain. And I can take this team forward. I can take us to win a World Cup, I believe," de Villiers said, after the defeat against India at The Oval. "I believed the same thing over here in this tournament and the last one here but that's what I believe. I love doing it."  Although de Villiers admitted that it was a "very poor batting performance" that saw South Africa slip from 76 without loss to 191 all out against India, he denied that they panicked.  Virat Kohli revealed that honest talks with his team members and laying out what is expected out of each one helped India bounce back after their defeat against Sri Lanka.  "You have to be honest. You have to sometimes say things that hurt," he said."You have to lay it out in front of them that this is what we did wrong, including me, and we need to take it on the chin and accept it and prove it.That's why we are chosen among millions of people to play at this level. You have to be good enough to do that for the country and you have to be good enough to bounce back, as well."   "You can't do the same mistakes over and over again. It's not about asking two, three players to do it. Until you have a team effort, you cannot win games, especially in conditions that you are not familiar with. Today was a team performance, " he added.  To follow Cricket on Duta: Add to your group: +919043016031  Type ðŸ‘IK6 to like this

ðŸ“° *IK6*: Captains SpeakðŸ—£ INDðŸ†šRSA  AB de Villiers affirmed his love for captaining the South Africa team and said he would like to continue as skipper till the 2019 World Cup, despite another failure for the Proteas in an ICC tournament.  "Because I'm a good captain. And I can take this team forward. I can take us to win a World Cup, I believe," de Villiers said, after the defeat against India at The Oval. "I believed the same thing over here in this tournament and the last one here but that's what I believe. I love doing it."  Although de Villiers admitted that it was a "very poor batting performance" that saw South Africa slip from 76 without loss to 191 all out against India, he denied that they panicked.  Virat Kohli revealed that honest talks with his team members and laying out what is expected out of each one helped India bounce back after their defeat against Sri Lanka.  "You have to be honest. You have to sometimes say things that hurt," he said."You have to lay it out in front of them that this is what we did wrong, including me, and we need to take it on the chin and accept it and prove it.That's why we are chosen among millions of people to play at this level. You have to be good enough to do that for the country and you have to be good enough to bounce back, as well."   "You can't do the same mistakes over and over again. It's not about asking two, three players to do it. Until you have a team effort, you cannot win games, especially in conditions that you are not familiar with. CTðŸ†: PAKðŸ†šSL : Sarfraz Does a MisbahðŸ˜Ž; Sloppy Sri Lanka EliminatedðŸ‘Š  PakistanðŸ‡µðŸ‡° went on a roller-coaster of a game against Sri Lanka & emerged victorsðŸŽ‰ to seal a spot in the semi-finals. After a superb bowling performance, they made a meal out of the mediocre target but managed to haul themselves over the lineðŸ˜ƒ.      Invited to bat first, Sri Lanka were bowled out for 236. Niroshan Dickwella top-scored for the Lankans but the heroes of the previous game, Mendis, Gunathilaka & Mathews failed to provide any supportðŸ˜Ÿ. PAK pacersâš¡ sizzled once again, picking up 8âƒ£ wickets between them.   Pakistan began the chase well, with debutant ðŸ’ªFakhar Zaman making a whirlwind half-century while Azhar Ali batted like he was wearing whites. Sri Lanka stormedðŸ‘Š back into the game in the middle overs with crucial wickets. Pakistan were reduced to 131/5 at the half-way stage and the match was tantalisingly poised. Nuwan Pradeepâš¡ had allrounder Imad Wasim nick one to the keeper and slogger Fahim Ashraf, guilty of backing up a long way at the non-striker's end, ran himself outðŸ˜¯. The scorecard read 162/7 at the end of 30 overs. Sri Lanka had a foot on the door.  Amidst the carnage, captain Sarfraz Ahmed kept calmðŸ™ and gave his team a glimmer of hope. He found an able partner in Mohammad Amir and the duo forged a fighting 75-run partnershipðŸ™Œ. They were helped by some atrocious fieldingðŸ˜– from the Lankans, who lost the plot - conceding overthrows, getting nutmegged in the outfield and dropping the simplest of catchesðŸ˜±. Sarfraz was dropped twice - Perera at mid off & Gunathilaka at square leg. The Pakistan skipper made them pay for squandering the opportunities and led his team to victoryðŸ‘.  It is has been a remarkable effort from Pakistan to bounce back after a resounding loss against IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ and qualify for the semis. England await them on the 14th of June. ðŸ“° *LE1*: BCCI to appoint ethics officer to look into conflict of interest issues  The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) is set to appoint an ethics officer to look into matters concerning conflict of interest which has bedevilled Indian cricket in recent years.  "All issues regarding conflict of interest will be referred to ethics officer appointed by the BCCI. He will be appointed soon. A lot of complaints regarding conflict of interest have been received," said Vinod Rai, chairman of the Supreme Court-appointed Committee of Administrators (COA).  Ramachandra Guha, the historian who recently tendered his resignation from the CoA, had raised the conflict of interest issue, citing several examples while coming down hard on the BCCI for failing to address the concerns. ðŸ“° *RO2*: Bangladesh Have Got Under India's Skin A Few Times, Says Mohammad Ashraful  Ahead of ICC Champions Trophy 2017 semi-final clash between India and Bangladesh, former captains Mohammad Ashraful and Habibul Bashar said on Wednesday that the defending champions will be under the pressure and not Bangladesh.  "We have previously reached Asia Cup final. But no doubt this is the biggest moment in the history of Bangladesh cricket. It's like mini World Cup. India are the defending champions it's no secret that they will be under more pressure. We have an experienced side and we need a team effort," the current selector said.      The 44-year-old said their bowlers will hold the key. However, Rohit Sharma will be the biggest 'threat'. His 137 in their 2015 World Cup quarterfinal win is "still fresh" in his mind.      Now-sidelined Ashraful also said pressure would be on India and added only one-two percent separates both the teams. Assalamalikum, This is to inform that we are building a New Cricket Team in Dubai, those who are interested to play can join us in our Dubai Royals Cricket Club.    We will be selecting our team members as per their performances in practice session. For those who are not fit to play will be provided with professional cricket coaching.  After establishment of a competitive team, we will start to play Tournaments in UAE and other Countries.   Interested to join the mighty Dubai Royals Cricket Club! Only need to pay Membership Fee of 100/- AED. For this membership fee you can avail the benefits as follows: 1. You will be a member of the Dubai Royals cricket club for the period of 1 month. 2. You can avail a free net practicing session. 3. Practice session will be at Dubai grounds, Ajman grounds and Sharjah grounds. 4. You can avail a free coaching session from national cricket player. 5. You can have an opportunity to play a Tournament with one of the UAE teams. 6. We will provide snacks as complimentary. 7.  We provide our kits for practice and matches but you can also bring your own if you want.  Note: 1. Any Nationality can participate / No age bar.       2. We will have different practice session/matches in different timings, according to team agreeed convenient time. ðŸ“° *XT6*: ðŸ‘©WWCðŸ†: IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ DefeatðŸ‘Š Sri LankaðŸ‡±ðŸ‡°  India 232/8 (Sharma 78, Raj 53; Weerakkody 3-28) bt Sri Lanka 216/7 (Manodara 61; Yadav 2-23, Goswami 2-26 ) by 16 runs  India joined Australia at the top of the table with a win over Sri Lanka to keep their 100% record intact. They successfully defended a total of 232 against the minnows to all but book their spot to the next round.  Choosing to bat on a slow pitch, the Indians had to work hard for their runs. A spectacular knock from Deepti Sharma at No.3, anchored the innings. Mithali Raj chipped in with a well compiled 53 and the duo guided the team to a competitive total. Sripali Weerakody removed opener Raut with the new ball before picking up two wickets in the death overs.  The Lankans started cautiously and looked to accelerate towards the end. The Indian bowlers tightened the screws in the middle overs but couldn't prise out wickets. Sri Lanka left themselves with 100 runs to get in the final ten overs with 7 wickets remaining. Dilani Manodara's measured knock kept her team in the hunt. However, Deepa Sharma foxed Mandora with some smart bowling at a crucial juncture and sent her back to the pavilion. After the fall of her wicket, Indian bowlers kept their nerve in the final overs to see out the win. This was Mithali Raj's troops narrowest win of the campaign so far. *New India coach Shastri promises more freedom for players*  New India cricket coach Ravi Shastri plans to adopt a more hands-off approach to the role than his predecessor Anil Kumble, with the 55-year-old saying he has no intention of trying to act as a tutor the players.  "At the highest level, cricketers are more or less settled," Shastri said. "So it is more to do with working on their mental strength, helping build their confidence, helping them stay organised in their daily activities as against tinkering with their style of play."  "It's not about 'tutoring' them about everything and telling them what and what not to do. There's very little coaching at the highest level. It's about fine-tuning and mentoring, about effective communication."  Shastri, who has served as team director in the past, enjoys a good rapport with Kohli and said he had no issues with players having more freedom off the field.  "Why should I change anyone's style, or for that matter, why should anyone change his own style of doing things? As long as there's a level of commitment, the hard yards are being put in and results are showing, why shouldn't there be fun?"  To read full article: https://goo.gl/5EqBnZ  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043002572*  Type ðŸ‘WK5 to like this  Type 'stop' to stop
*CoA Wants Kapil Dev As Part Of Steering Committee For Players Body*  The Committee of Administrators (COA) has recommended former India captain Kapil Dev's name as a part of the four-member steering committee that will help in the formation of Players' Association as per Lodha Panel Recommendation. Two other recommended members are former Test opener Anshuman Gaekwad and wicketkeeper Bharath Reddy, while GK Pillai is the third one. The Lodha Panel in its recommendation initially wanted a steering committee with GK Pillai, Mohinder Amarnath, Diana Edulji and Anil Kumble.      The COA in its fourth Status Report submitted to Supreme Court has intimated the Apex Court that Mohinder Amarnath and Kumble have "communicated their inability to be part of the Steering Committee" and Edulji can't be a part as she is a member of COA.   While Pillai remains in the steering committee, Kapil is a big name that COA has recommended.  To read full article: https://goo.gl/ZdoRaH  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919042016120*  Type ðŸ‘WL1 to like this  Type 'stop' to stop
*Australia seal semifinal spot with convincing win*  India 226/7 in 50 overs (Poonam Raut 106, Mithali Raj 69; Ellyse Perry 2-37) lost to Australia 227/2 in 45.1 overs (Meg Lanning 76*, Perry 60*) by 8 wickets.  The ICC Women's World Cup group clash between Australia and India will be, and should be, remembered for several reasons. It saw Mithali Raj take over Charlotte Edwards as the highest run-getter in ODI history and also become the first woman to score 6000 runs in the history of the 50-over game.  Raj's 69 and a magnificent 106 from Poonam Raut, though, wasn't enough to stop the Australian juggernaut as they sealed an eight-wicket win to jump to the top of the table. Set 226, Meg Lanning scored an unbeaten 76 while handy contributions from Ellyse Perry (60 not out) and Beth Mooney ensured Australia's smooth passage over the line.  The loss also makes things fairly simple for India. A win against New Zealand in their last game will seal a semifinal spot and a loss will knock them out of the tournament. While Australia's victory also ensured that South Africa qualified for the semi-final as well.  To read full article: https://goo.gl/XVW2ua  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919042009288*  Type ðŸ‘WK6 to like this  Type 'stop' to stop

*Sciver and Beaumont fire England into semi-finals*  England 284 for 9 (Sciver 129, Beaumont 93, Kerr 4-51) beat New Zealand 209 (Bates 44, Perkins 43*, Hartley 3-43) by 75 runs  Nat Sciver struck her second century of an increasingly formidable World Cup campaign, as England's women marched into the semi-finals with a 75-run victory over New Zealand at Derby. With Tammy Beaumont falling short of a century of her own, England's fourth-wicket pair added 170 in 27 overs to rescue the team from a top-order wobble, before their slow bowlers snuffed out a reply that flickered briefly, Alex Hartley starring with 3 for 43. *Jason Gillespie named interim coach of PNG*  Papua New Guinea have appointed former Australia pacer and Yorkshire coach Jason Gillespie as their interim coach, in a bid to make a harder push towards qualification for the 2019 World Cup. Cricket Papua New Guinea's chief executive Greg Campbell confirmed the development and stated that Gillespie, who replaces former mentor of the side, Dipak Patel, had been roped in for a 12-month period.  Gillespie had recently been named the coach of Australia A, but with the tour of South Africa not going ahead owing to the ongoing pay dispute, the 42-year-old decided to take up the short-term opportunity with PNG, and that he'd heard a lot of good things about the team. *Morkel ready to own no-ball issues*  Morne Morkel is prepared to own his no-ball problem, but that doesn't mean he will be changing the length of his run-up in the lead-up to the second Test between England and South Africa at Trent Bridge on Friday (July 14).  At a crucial juncture in the 1st Test that the Proteas went on to lose, Morkel bowled Ben Stokes off a no-ball. Remarkably its the 13th time that Morkel has got a wicket off a no-ball in Tests.  "I need a lot of rhythm and timing is crucial for me. The more I've bowled in a Test match the better my timing and my feel at the crease was," said Morkel. "Unfortunately I did bowl that no-ball and that's the sort of thing you don't want to give quality players like Joe Root and 'Stokesy' a life. You're going to get punished for that.  "The only thing I can do is keep on working on that; work on getting the foot behind the line. It's a rush of blood to the head, wanting to create something with the older, softer ball. But I can't make my run-up longer, I can't make it shorter. I'm just going to stick with it." *Shastri to pitch for Bharath Arun despite Zaheer's presence*  Ravi Shastri is likely to pitch for the return of bowling coach Bharath Arun despite the presence of Zaheer Khan in their ranks.  Shastri's choice of bowling coach was always Arun and it is now apparent that Cricket Advisory Committee did not take Shastri into confidence while recommending Zaheer as the bowling coach although his role would be similar to that of Rahul Dravid - that of a consultant.      It has been learnt that Zaheer is unlikely to give around 250 days a year that a full-time bowling coach will be required to and may not be available for more than 100 days. It may also be mentioned that Zaheer's salary package has not yet been inked as negotiations are still on. *Erapalli Prasanna disappointed with CAC's drama on Ravi Shastri's selection*  Former India off-spinner Erapalli Prasanna on Thursday said he is "disappointed" with the three-member Cricket Advisory Committee (CAC) for opting to appoint Ravi Sashtri as the new head coach for the Indian team.  The CAC comprises of former cricketers, Sourav Ganguly, Sachin Tendulkar & VVS Laxman.  "I am disappointed with the CAC. They are three legendary cricketers and they should have taken so long to name the coach. A consensus should have been reached, and from what I have been reading, they could not come to a unanimous decision and it was all done at the last minute," said Prasanna.  Prasanna, 77, felt that the CAC should have defined the roles of the new additions to the coaching staff more accurately, adding that Shastri is just a team manager and that "coach" is just a name. He shared his doubts whether Sanjay Bangar will have a role in the coaching staff in the future. *Anurag Thakur Tenders Unconditional Apology In Supreme Court*  Former BCCI president Anurag Thakur on Thursday tendered a fresh 'unconditional' and 'unequivocal' apology in the Supreme Court, saying it was never his intention to undermine the majesty of the apex court. Thakur, a senior BJP leader and a Member of Parliament from Hamirpur in Himachal Pradesh, was asked by the apex court on July 7 to tender an apology in explicit terms to get relief from the contempt proceedings initiated against him.      "I humbly submit that it was never the intention of the deponent to undermine the majesty of this court and since unintentionally some kind of misinformation and miscommunication has occured, I unhesitatingly tender my unconditional and unequivocal apology to this court," he said in his affidavit filed on Thursday. *Virat Kohli trolled for posting Punam Raut's picture while congratulating Mithali Raj*  Virat Kohli lauded India women's cricket team captain Mithali Raj after she created history by breaching the 6000-run mark in one-day internationals. However, this was not before he wrongly posted a picture of India opener Punam Raut on his Facebook page while congratulating Mithali on her achievement.      Kohli was trolled for his goof-up and he later removed the post and the picture from Facebook.      The 34-year-old Mithali became the first to reach the landmark in women's ODIs, surpassing England's Charlotte Edwards(5992 runs). *SLC offers Hambantota groundstaff cash, clothes after uniform fiasco*  Sri Lanka Cricket (SLC) on Wednesday offered cash and new clothes to temporary groundsmen, who were forced to handover their uniforms after the fifth One-Day International between Sri Lanka and Zimbabwe.  The groundsman at Hambantota's MRI Cricket Stadium, who were daily wage workers of the region, were given uniforms to wear during the match. This practice of giving uniforms to the local workers, who are called in to put covers on the entire ground in case of a rain was started recently. But on Monday (July 10), they were asked to return their clothes before leaving the venue. Many of them were reported to have been paid only after the trousers were returned, leaving them stripped down to their underwear.  One of the groundsman said, "They only paid us for our three days worth of work after taking our clothes."  Another one added: "They hadn't told us to come prepared with another set of clothes. They asked us to hand over the trousers, so we had no choice but to do that."  In the aftermath of the incident, SLC formally apologised to "those subjected to this ignominy". *David Peever slams Australian players' union for 'reckless' tactics*  Cricket Australia chairman David Peever has hit out at Australian Cricketers' Association (ACA), stating that Cricket Australia has been insulted and disrespected as the players continue to be at loggerheads with the cricket board. In his column in The Australian, Peever wrote of ACA's 'campaign of sustained ferocity', claiming that CA's offer on the table was 'very generous'.  "CA has put what in any normal circumstances would be regarded as a very generous offer. The ACA has responded by not only rejecting that proposal (and recent concessions) out of hand, but by launching a campaign of such sustained ferocity that anyone could be forgiven for thinking CA was proposing the reintroduction of slavery rather than healthy pay rises," he wrote.  Peever went on to explain how and why ACA's 'reckless strategy' would only damage the game. He also claimed that rumours of CA being motivated by some extreme industrial relations agenda were a complete myth and intentionally made up. ðŸ“° *DF9*: *Why Virender Sehwag missed out on coach's job*  Skipper Virat Kohli and the rest of the Indian team which was categorically against the idea of continuing with Anil Kumble as the head coach of the team, had no problems whatsoever with any of the other candidates applying for the role.  They had made it clear that they would not interfere with the Cricket Advisory Committee's (CAC) decision.   This comes to light after a week of chaos and drama that ensued following interviews of five candidates held by the CAC earlier this week.  Former India opener Virender Sehwag, a mentor with the Kings XI Punjab franchise in the IPL, had Kohli's complete backing and would've been a front-runner to grab the role if not for certain conditions.  The two men from Delhi could've well turned their familiarity with each other into a professional relationship if not for Sehwag's proposal to bring along with him a team of support staff that would include physiotherapist Amit Tyagi and Kings XI Punjab assistant coach Mithun Manhas along with him.  It is here that Shastri managed to become the front-runner, considering he was willing to have a more inclusive approach as far as he, the skipper and the team members were concerned. ðŸ“° *NX6*: *Wasim Akram leaves Islamabad United for new PSL franchise*  Legendary fast bowler Wasim Akram has left Islamabad United in order to join new franchise of Multan for the upcoming third edition of the Pakistan Super League (PSL).  Confirming the news, Akram's manager Arsalan Shah said that the former pacer has decided to move on after two successful seasons with United.  "We have left Islamabad United and are officially signing with another franchise this week," he said.  When quizzed as to which team Akram is expected to join, Arsalan said that they are negotiating with many franchises, with special mention given to Multan. *Rahane & Pujara ConsolidateðŸ’ª Indian InningsðŸ‘*  ðŸµTea: Day 1  ðŸ”°IND 238/3 (58 ov) (Pujara 89*, Perera 1/54)  By the end of the second session on day 1 of the 2âƒ£nd Test between India and Sri Lanka, the visitors are threatening to bat Sri Lanka out of the contest again, having reached 238/3.  India started the session at 101/1 but saw two quick wickets fall, the first a piece of misunderstanding between Pujara and Rahul (57) which ended up with the latter being stranded in the middle of the pitch. Rahul was looking good and was understandably upset at the dismissal. However, Virat Kohli was unable to carry on for long and fell to a deceptive quicker ball from Herath, cutting him to slip.  But Rahane (40*) joined forces with Pujara and went on to steady the ship and raised an unbeaten 105-run stand. If Sri Lanka do not get a wicket soon enough, India will be in a position to dictate terms, just like in the first Test.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919282201103*  Type ðŸ‘QA8 to like this

*SLðŸ†šIND: Sri LankaðŸ‡±ðŸ‡° to Follow on After 1st Session CollapseðŸ˜ž*  Day 3: Lunch   India - 622/9d   Sri Lanka 183 (Dickwela 51; Ashwin 5-69, Shami 2-13)  SL trail by 439 runs.     Sri Lanka were bowled out in the morning session and have been asked to follow on. With puffs of dust exploding from time to time, the hosts couldn't be facing a more skilled duo than Ashwin & Jadeja, who have risen to the top by becoming experts on such surfaces over the past couple of years. But they were also let down by their shot selection.     Dinesh Chandimal couldn't blame the pitch for his dismissal as he carelessly swept the ball in the air and Pandya at backward squareleg completed the catch. Kushal Mendis spooned a catch to mid-on and Sri Lanka were 4 down with very few runs added to the overnight score. Angelo Mathews and Niroshan Dickwella counter-attacked by looking to throw the spinners of their lengths. Their onslaught worked for a brief period as the pair raised 53 runs in 8 overs for the 5th wicket. The partnership was cut short by a blinder of a catch from Pujara at leg gully to send Mathews back. Dickwella continued to live by the sword and notched his 2nd half-century of the series off just 44 deliveries. Jadeja picked up his 150th career wicket, when he castled Dhananjeya with sharp turner from around the wicket.  Dickwella's adventurous knock came to end when he attempted a ramp shot off Shami and play onto his stumps. The pacer picked up another wicket in the same over, disturbing Herath's stumps with pacey yorker. Ashwin picked up the final 2 wickets to complete his fifer.  India have enforced a follow-on. The writing is on the wall for the hosts. Will Sri Lanka last the dayâ‰  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919042009827*  Type ðŸ‘XL6 to like this

*Karunaratne & MendisðŸ‘ Keep India at Bayâœ‹*  ðŸµTea - Day 3  ðŸ”°SL 183 & 118/1 (Karunaratne 55*, Mendis 61*, Yadav 1/17) trail India 622/9 by 321 runs  In the second session of the 2nd Test between India and Sri Lanka in Colombo, we have finally seen some fight from the home team. it made for a welcoming change from the pathetic collapse in the morning session where they lost eight wickets and were forced to follow on.  Though, for a fleeting moment, it looked as if the second innings would end quickly when Umesh Yadav managed to spear one in through the defense of Upul Tharanga. But Dimuth Karunaratne (55*) and Kusal Mendis (61*) joined forces to remind one and all that Sri Lanka were not done yet.  Both of them added 111 runs in an enterprising partnership which is incidentally their highest in the series so far. Mendis was particularly effective against Ashwin and Jadeja with his sweeps. While SL are still 321 runs short of India's total and might well succumb to an innings defeat yet, this show of spunk has been a fresh breath in a series that has been so one-sided.  What will the third session bring on a pitch that is deteriorating every moment? Let's wait and see.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043012770*  Type ðŸ‘XZ9 to like this

Great india ... Win series
It's an innings victory for India. A late collapse from Sri Lanka here. Pradeep was the last man to fall, top edging a sweep off Ashwin as India go 2-0 up in the series.
India has won the match.
*Innings Win for IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ After Late Lankan CollapseðŸ™†*  ðŸ”° IND 622/9 beat SL 183 & 386 by an innings and 53 runs  India have claimed the three-match series against Sri Lanka after attaining an unassailable 2-0 lead after defeating the home team by an innings and 53 runs.  After being asked to follow on, Sri Lanka made a mighty fighting effort in their second innings to cut down a huge lead of 439 runs and almost forced India to bat again. At lunch on day 4, it seemed Mathews (36) and Karunaratne (141) would go on for Lanka. But Jadeja came into his own and got one to spit and jump at Karunaratne, ending his stay. Mathews soon fell over after edging a cut. Having been dealt two huge blows, Sri Lanka unravelled quickly with Jadeja claiming a five-wicket haul. Hardik Pandya also chipped in with a wicket while Ashwin picked the last wicket to fall.  Though Sri Lanka's last 6 wickets fell for just 76 runs, they can take a lot of heart from the fact that they managed to put some sort of resistance against the Indians who have had a far too easy a time in this series. Virat Kohli and co. were made to sweat for a while, though it was not helped by Kohli's poor catching in the slip cordon.  At the end of the day, India will feel happy that they did not have to bat again.  â­MoM: Ravindra Jadeja  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043009615*  Type ðŸ‘CC1 to like this

ðŸ“° *IW4*: *ENGðŸ†šRSA: England Closing in On a Historic WinðŸŽ‰*  Day 4 - Tea  South Africa 226 & 182/6 (Amla 83, Faf 60*) trail England 362 & 243 (Moeen Ali 75*, Joe Root 49; Morne Morkel 4-41, Duanne Olivier 3-38) by 198 runs.  South Africa were handed an early blow on the 4th day in their pursuit of a massive target in the final Test at Old Trafford as Dean Elgar, Heino Kuhn and Temba Bavuma departed before Lunch. Chasing 380, the visitors headed into the 40-minute break needing another 340 runs with seven wickets in hand.  England's new-ball duo Anderson & Broad posed plenty of questions to the South African top-order. Broad had Elgar nick one to the wicket-keeper and his partner ended Kuhn's nervy stay and possibly his international career with his trademark outswinger that the South African edged to first slip. Toby Roland-Jones successfully reviewed the final ball before Lunch to send Temba Bavuma back to the pavilion.  However, South Africa's most experienced batsmen, Amla & Faf du Plessis forged a 123-run partnership to launch a fightback. A 3-wicket burst from Moeen Ali before the Tea interval dashed any hopes of a South African revival. The off spinner trapped the well set Amla LBW and then claimed the wickets of QDK & Thanis de Bruyne - both edging the offspinner to slip. With a long tail(no Philander & no Morris), England are favourites to secure the win and end the 19-year wait to secure a series triumph over their opponents.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043009326*  Type ðŸ‘IW4 to like this  *Collect ðŸ“¯ DUTA ðŸ“¯  Points ðŸ’°* You have *101 duta points* and are at level *ðŸ™‡â€â™€ï¸Apprentice*. ðŸ“° *KN1*: *'Competent' pace battery will bring more overseas success for India: Ian Bishop*  Ian Bishop feels that the current pace attack of the Indian cricket team, which is very competent, will help the team to be more successful in foreign conditions.      Bishop was asked about his opinion of the current Indian pace attack, to which he replied, "It's good, it's good. Mohammed Shami, Umesh Yadav, Bhuvneshwar Kumar, Jasprit Bumrah - they're all good," he said. "They all bring different skill-sets. Bumrah's changes of pace and yorkers, Bhuvneshwar swings the ball and he's had to adapt his game to different pitches and conditions now. He's put on a little bit of pace too. Shami and Yadav are very sharp and quick. So it's competent."      The West Indian, who now officiates as cricketer commentator, further asserted that the current pace attack of the Indian team would help them not only to be good at home, where they have ace off-spinner R Ashwin, but to be better overseas too. ðŸ“° *ND8*: *Ravi Shastri Sets a New Target for Team India*  Head coach Ravi Shastri is looking to keep team India motivated after the men in blue took an unassailable 2-0 lead in the Test series against Sri Lanka. India have managed to breach the 600-run mark in both the games and Shastri believes that his team needs to ensure that they hit this mark more often that not, in home & away games.   "India can certainly surpass Australia's record of scoring over 600 runs most number of times. I am sure this team will surely achieve this. When, I can't say. Whether this year, next year or some other time. But I would be happy if it is done during my tenure as a coach with the team," Shastri said.   Australia have score 600 or more 32 times in Tests. India is 2nd on that list, reaching that total 29 times.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917550031685*  Type ðŸ‘ND8 to like this

ðŸ“° *WM4*: *England AnnounceðŸ“¢ SquadðŸ“œ for 1st Test Against the Windies*  Surrey's opening batsman, Mark Stoneman is set to make his Test debut against a pink ball next week, after being named in a 13-man England squad for the 1st Test against West Indies at Edgbaston, the first day-night Test to be staged in this country.  Also in the frame for a debut is the 20-year-old legspinner, Mason Crane, who has been handed an opportunity to press for a place on this winter's Ashes tour. He replaces his Hampshire team-mate, Liam Dawson.  All-rounder Chris Woakes has returned to the Test fold after recovering from his injury.  Squad for 1st Test:    Joe Root (capt), Moeen Ali, James Anderson, Jonny Bairstow (wk), Stuart Broad, Alastair Cook, Mason Crane, Dawid Malan, Toby Roland-Jones, Ben Stokes, Mark Stoneman, Tom Westley, Chris Woakes  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043012621*  Type ðŸ‘WM4 to like this  *Collect ðŸ“¯ DUTA ðŸ“¯  Points ðŸ’°* You have *8 duta points* and are at level *ðŸ¤¸â€â™€ï¸Citizen*. ðŸ“° *WM7*: *CPL, PSL in talks to collaborate for annual series*  The Caribbean Premier League is in talks with the Pakistan Super League to create an annual series of matches between the winners of the two leagues. The CPL hopes that the idea will give the league more context and ultimately make it more commercially viable.  It is envisaged that the series, which could could be launched next year, would feature 3 matches between the champions of the two leagues, to take place just before the 2018 CPL season. The United States is viewed as an attractive location to stage the games, given the large number of cricket fans from both Pakistan and the Caribbean there.  "It would make the most sense, to have a three-game series over four days," said Pete Russell, the chief operating officer of the CPL. "You have to look into all the practicalities - the commercial viability of it. The US would be a great place to play games like that. There's definitely a feeling here that there's a great Pakistani community, and obviously a great Caribbean community as well, so it'd be an interesting place to play it, wouldn't it?" ðŸ“° *WM8*: *USA could co-host 2018 Women's World T20 with West Indies*  The United States could co-host the Women's World Twenty20 next November, bringing an ICC global event to America for the first time. Prospects of matches being held at the Lauderhill ground, in Florida, are "well over 50%," according to Fara Gorsi, the ICC Americas development manager. Johnny Grave, the chief executive of Cricket Windies (CWI), who are the designated hosts of the tournament, is also keen to explore the prospect.  "It's something that we're looking to do for sure," said Gorsi. "In the Americas there's a lack of women's cricket - we have the USA team but we need to develop cricket, so having women's cricket (event) featuring here as co-hosts would be massive kudos for ICC Americas and also for cricket in general for women." *Ravichandran Ashwin, Ravindra Jadeja likely to be rested for limited-overs series vs Sri Lanka*  The Indian team management and national selectors may rest Ravichandran Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja from the limited-overs matches, starting August 20.  It is expected that pacer Mohammed Shami will also be rested from the ODI series as his workload needs to be monitored.      Chairman of selectors MSK Prasad is in Kandy to track the performances while his colleague Devang Gandhi is in South Africa with the A team. They will be on conference call with third member Sarandeep Singh on August 13 to pick the squad. *Muralitharan refutes Ranatungaâ€™s 2011 World Cup final match-fixing claims*  Sri Lanka cricket legend Muttiah Muralitharan completely denied allegations of match-fixing made by former captain Arjuna Ranatunga, saying that there were no instructions to lose the 2011 World Cup final against India.  In an interview, the 45-year-old Muralitharan bluntly said, "Indiaâ€™s was the best team and ours was the second best team in the tournament.â€  Muralitharan further went on to state that injuries sustained by both himself and all-rounder Angelo Mathews were the main reason behind Sri Lankaâ€™s loss in the final against India at the Wankhede Stadium, in Mumbai.  â€œWe had a good opportunity to win in the final, but two things happened. I had a groin injury in the semi final and Angelo Mathews, who was among runs was completely out (final) because he was injured,â€ said Muralitharan. "The batsmen were scoring runs but the middle order batsmen didn't click in few matches and the selectors made 3-4 changes and it was far than a regular team."  Murali further went on to state that dew was a major factor for the Sri Lankan players on that fateful night at the Wankhede Stadium.  "Within 15 overs dew came and they could do nothing. There was no match-fixing but Mathews' injury, miscalculation (on dew factor) cost us the World Cup final,â€ he said. â€œBut we can't take away credit from India." *Series lost, but not over: Chandimal promises a fight to avoid whitewash*  Hosting India in Galle and Colombo, Sri Lanka didn't receive the best of return gifts from the visitors. India notched up 600-plus totals in both the matches and then ran through Sri Lanka's batting line-up to register two convincing wins, and take an unassailable 2-0 lead in the three-match series. The hosts will now go to Pallekele, sans their best players - Rangana Herath & Nuwan Pradeep - and hope to avoid a whitewash.  Skipper Dinesh Chandimal addressed the media ahead of the third Test and spoke about the preparations and plans for the final match.  "Series is not yet over. As a captain, I don't like to lose. It does not matter whether if it's the world's number one team or number eighth team, I want to win. We're giving our full effort to that but we cannot control the ultimate result, " declared the Sri Lankan skipper.   He was coy on the batting order and the changes to be made to the side. *Du Plessis warns SA against wholesale changes*  South Africa's Test captain Faf du Plessis has asked their next head coach not to make wholesale changes to the backroom staff.  Last week, reports emerged that Russell Domingo was on his way out and that CSA were looking at replacing him with Ottis Gibson, the England bowling coach.  There have been suggestions of changes to the support staff as well but Du Plessis threw his support behind the incumbents Neil McKenzie (batting coach), Charl Langeveldt (bowling coach) and Claude Henderson (spin coach).  "In an ideal situation, you'd like to make as little change as possible so it's not wholesale changes," he said. "A whole new coaching staff would come in and it would take a while to get to know everyone.  "If there was a suggestion I could make is for whoever, if it was Ottis, to come in and see for himself what the team requires. If he decides that there needs to be changes, then he decides that over a period of time. Our technical coaches, I think, have been doing a very good job." *Coach Darren Lehmann says, Pay-war break may benefit Aussies*  Darren Lehmann promised Australia won't be underprepared for their tour of Bangladesh after a pay dispute left them temporarily unemployed -- and said the enforced break may have even done them good.  Despite having only a week to prepare for their first Test tour of Bangladesh in more than a decade, Lehmann said the disruption was not a concern.  "Until you get there you don't know, but we're squeezing enough in this next week, and guys have been doing stuff with their (home) states," Lehmann said. "Even through the MoU (pay negotiations) they were training and preparing as though they were playing. So in terms of fitness, they are probably ahead of the game, they're really strong and fit which is really pleasing. Now it's just getting their skills up to the required level before we leave." *ICC Women's World Cup 2017 watched by over 180 million cricket buffs*  The recently concluded ICC Women's World Cup in England saw a record coverage with over more than 180 million people being estimated to have watched the prestigious quadrennial tournament and there was an almost 300% increase in viewing hours in comparison to the last edition in 2013.      The hosts England won the World Cup defeating India in a thriller by nine runs in the final played at the Lord's on July 23.      There was significant growth in audiences in all territories, but particularly impressive was an eight-fold increase in viewing hours in South Africa and a huge increase in viewers in India, particularly in rural areas, since 2013.   The ICC's decision to ensure that every match was available for viewing either on television or via live-streaming as part of its commitment to the global growth of the women's game has paid dividends.   An extraordinary 156 million people viewed the event in India, of which 80 million was rural reach and 126 million were for the final alone. India's fine performances contributed to a 500% increase in viewing hours in their country. *3rd Test Preview: Sri LankaðŸ‡±ðŸ‡° HopeðŸ™ to Avoid Whitewash*  The series of agony will end in 5 days for Sri Lanka. Going by the last Test, maybe sooner. Having been outplayed by India in the both the previous Tests, Sri Lanka would hope to salvage pride at Pallekele.  The hosts are without their best spinner (Herath) and best pacer (Pradeep) and are looking for a new strategy for this game. After choosing an all spin attack on the dust bowl at SSC, they might be inclined to pick 3 pacers in Lahiru Kumara, Vishwa Fernando & Dushmantha Chameera. Their batsmen have displayed grit, albeit in the 3rd and 4th innings.   Virat Kohli has announced that there will be no major changes to the XI. With Jadeja suspended, the choice is between wrist spinner Kuldeep and half-batsman Axar Patel. India could possibly mirror Sri Lanka and name 4 seamers in their lineup.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397692171*  Type ðŸ‘AJ3 to like this

*SLðŸ†šIND: IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ Openers At It AgainðŸ’¥*  Day 1 - Lunch  India - 134/0 (Dhawan 64*, Rahul 67*)  As has been the norm in this series, India opted to bat and their openers went about their job of destroying the psyche of the Sri Lankan bowlers. At Lunch on Day 1, India sit pretty at 134/0, boasting of a session run-rate of 4.96.  India made only one change for this dead rubber. Kuldeep Yadav replacing suspended Ravindra Jadeja. Injury-plagued Sri Lanka named 3 changes - spinner Lakshan Sandakan, pacers Lahiru Kumara and Vishwa Fernando.  The opening duo of Shikhar Dhawan and KL Rahul toyed with the bowling while Dinesh Chandimal prayed for a miracle or a mistake from the two attacking batsmen. It was all too easy for the batsmen as there were lot of freebies on offer and they cashed in. Both notched their half-centuries in good time.  Before KL Rahul reached his 50, he had a reprieve when he was dropped at mid-on by Kumara. He was running back and reached the ball but couldn't hold on.  It has been Groundhog series for Sri Lanka, waking up to the same kind of opening day. They need to be more disciplined with their bowling to turn the tide.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917338894267*  Type ðŸ‘BB3 to like this

*SLðŸ†šIND : Bowlersâš¡ Stallâœ‹ India on Opening Day*  Day - 1 : Stumps   India - 329/6 (Dhawan 119, Rahul 85; Pushpakumara 3-40)  Finally, a hard-fought day where the spoils were shared between the two teams in this series.    In the morning, Indian batsmen threatened the usual - scoring a mammoth score at a rapid rate. But a resurgent bowling performance from Sri Lanka in the afternoon and evening sessions kept them in check.  After opting to bat, India made a terrific start with their fluent openers, Rahul & Dhawan smashing fifties in the first session. Left-arm spinner Pushpakumara broke the partnership in the 2nd session with a well-flighted delivery, that forced a false short from Rahul. Dhawan powered to his 2nd century of the series before a superb catch by skipper Chandimal at squareleg sent him back to the pavillion. The hosts then got the prized wicket of Pujara(8) cheaply. 3 wickets in one session were unheard riches for Sri Lanka. Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane looked to rebuild the innings but both(42, 17) failed to capitalize on their starts.    R Ashwin hung around with Wriddhiman Saha and played for stumps. However, left-armer Vishwa Fernando got the all-rounder(31) with the 2nd new ball just before close of play.  Hardik Pandya(1*) & Saha(13*) are the unbeaten batsmen.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919940639039*  Type ðŸ‘BV8 to like this

ðŸ“° *BX4*: *India vs Sri Lanka: ODI Team To Be Selected On Sunday*  The Indian team for the five-match ODI series against Sri Lanka will be selected on Sunday evening. While chief selector MSK Prasad is currently in Sri Lanka to track the performances, the Board of Control for Cricket in India's (BCCI) acting secretary Amitabh Chaudhury is headed for Kandy. Devang Gandhi is in South Africa with the 'A' team. Sarandeep Singh and Gandhi will join the meeting through Skype. The five-match ODI series begins on August 20 at Dambulla and the last one is on September 3 at Colombo.   There were rumours that Virat Kohli wouldn't be playing the ODI series but the Indian captain put all those to rest on Friday. "Who said I am not playing? I don't know where this came from, but I have no problems in playing," Kohli answered to a query on team selection during a press conference. ðŸ“° *BX8*: *Sri Lanka to host World XI in charity T20*  Sri Lanka Cricket (SLC) will host a charity match between World XI and Sri Lanka XI on September 8 in a Twenty20 match scheduled to be played at the R. Premadasa Stadium.  The match that will be played two days after the one off T20I between Sri Lanka and India, will feature a host of present and retired overseas stars.  The funds collected from the game will proceed towards the victims of the recent flood and the patients suffering from the chronic kidney disease that has caused more than 20,000 deaths in the last 20 years.  The Sri Lanka XI will comprise a mixture of current and former players. *SLðŸ†šIND : Pandya's TonðŸ’¯ Powers IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³*  Day - 2 :Lunch  India 487/9 (Dhawan 119, Rahul, 85, Pandya 108* ; Sandakkan 4-132)  Not even an extended 1st session was enough for Sri Lanka to bowl out India. Hardik Pandya in the company of Kuldeep & Umesh Yadav punished the hosts, as the visitors added 158 runs in 32 overs.  Left-arm pacer got rid of Wriddhiman Saha(16) early. The keeper-batsman flirted with a length ball outside off and handed a simple catch to gully. Despite the early wicket, Sri Lanka didn't attack to try and dispose of the tail. Their conservative approach allowed a 67-run partnership for the 8th wicket between Kuldeep Yadav & Hardik Pandya that lasted 20 overs. Pandya was initially more restrained in his approach and played sensibly. Lakshan Sandakan broke the stand, by having his counterpart(26) nick one behind. The Chinaman bowler then held on to a return catch to send Shami(8) back. That wicket triggered Pandya to switch to power hitting mode. He went after Pushpakumara and smashed 24 runs in one over. Shocked by the onslaught, Chandimal reacted by having 9 boundary riders. Pandya farmed the strike wisely and notched his maiden century. His innings was adorned with 8 fours and 7 sixes.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919042015975*  Type ðŸ‘EI5 to like this

Pandya was initially more restrained in his approach and played sensibly. Lakshan Sandakan broke the stand, by having his counterpart(26) nick one behind. *SLðŸ†šIND:Sri LankaðŸ‡±ðŸ‡° on the Ropes Once AgainðŸ˜Ÿ*  Day 2: Stumps  India - 483(Dhawan 119, Pandya 108; Sandakan 5-132)   SL 138(Chandimal 42; Kuldeep 4-40) & 19/1 (Umesh Yadav 1-3)  India enforced follow on for the 2nd consecutive time this series and are on course to complete a whitewash against Sri Lanka. At the end of Day 2, Sri Lanka trail India by 333 runs with 9 wickets in hand, following on.  Resuming the day at 329/6, India reached a formidable total thanks largely to Hardik Pandya's terrific maiden century. The all-rounder who batted patiently for the most part of his innings, cut loose after the fall of the 9th wicket. He was the final Indian wicket to fall, with Chinaman bowler Sandakan completing his maiden Test fifer.  Sri Lanka's chase got off to a bad start as both openers Karunaratne & Tharanga were undone by some accurate bowling by Mohammad Shami. Some good bit of fielding resulted in Kushal Mendis being run-out and after that, the rest of the batting just fell away. Captain Chandimal offered a modicum of resistance by India soon bowled out the home side for a paltry total of 135. Kuldeep Yadav was India's best bowler, finishing with figures of 4-40.  Following on, Sri Lanka lost Tharanga for the 2nd time in the day. The southpaw was bowled by Umesh Yadav. His partner Karunaratne (12*) and night watchman Pushpakumara(0*) held fort till close of play.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917550046493*  Type ðŸ‘EW9 to like this

ðŸ“° *FJ8*: *IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ AnnounceðŸ“¢ Limited Overs SquadðŸ“œ*  Many stars including Yuvraj Singh, Mohammed Shami, R Ashwin, Ravindra Jadeja and Umesh Yadav have not been picked for the upcoming ODI series and lone T20I against Sri Lanka.  Fringe players like Shardul Thakur, Yuzvendra Chahal, Axar Patel and KL Rahul have been named in the 15-man squad.  India play five ODIs and one T20I starting August 20 in Dambulla.  Here is the squad for the 5-match ODI series against Sri Lanka:   Virat Kohli(c), Shikhar Dhawan, Rohit Sharma (vc), KL Rahul, Manish Pandey, Ajinkya Rahane, MS Dhoni, Kedar Jadhav, Hardik Pandya, Axar Patel, Yuzvendra Chahal, Shardul Thakur, Bhuvneshwar Kumar, Kuldeep Yadav, Jasprit Bumrah.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397690294*  Type ðŸ‘FJ8 to like this  *Collect ðŸ“¯ DUTA ðŸ“¯  Points ðŸ’°* You have *88 duta points* and are at level *ðŸ™‡â€â™€ï¸Apprentice*. ðŸ“° *FJ7*: *Hardik's whirlwind ton knocks over records and Sri Lanka*  ðŸ”°26 runs by Hardik off the 116th over of the innings bowled by Malinda Pushpakumara is the most runs scored off a single over by an Indian batsman in Test cricket. He eclipsed 24 runs scored by Sandeep Patil off Bob Willis in Manchester in 1982, and by Kapil Dev off Eddie Hemmings at Lord's in 1990.  ðŸ”°24 The previous most runs scored off an over in a Test in Sri Lanka - by Sanath Jayasuriya off James Anderson in Kandy in 2007. 26 conceded by Pushpakumara is the joint-most by any Sri Lankan bowler in Tests alongside Suranga Lakmal who conceded 26 to Brendon McCullum in Christchurch in 2014.  ðŸ”°5 Indian players who scored their maiden first-class hundred in a Test match - Vijay Manjrekar, Kapil Dev, Ajay Ratra, Harbhajan Singh and now Hardik. His previous highest score in first-class cricket was 90 for Baroda against Railways in Delhi in 2015 - it was just his third first-class match.      ðŸ”°107 runs scored by Hardik is the most by an Indian batsman before Lunch on any day of a Test. The previous most was 99 runs by Virender Sehwag against West Indies in Gros Islet in 2006.  ðŸ”°86 balls taken by Hardik to reach his hundred is the second fastest for an Indian player away from home, after the 78-ball hundred by Virender Sehwag against West Indies in Gros Islet in 2006. It is the joint-fastest hundred by a visiting player in Sri Lanka alongside Wasim Akram's 86-ball effort against the hosts in 2000. ðŸ“° *FJ6*: *India will tour South Africa early next year, says Rahul Johri*  BCCI CEO Rahul Johri confirmed on Sunday that India will travel to South Africa for a full tour early next year.   With Sri Lanka scheduled to play a return tour to India in November-December, which is part of the ICC future tour program, there were some doubts over the Indian team's visit to South Africa.      "The South Africa tour is on. There is some back and forth on dates, but it will be a full tour and that has been locked in," Johri said.  The 2017-18 is be a busy season for the Indian cricketers as Australia, New Zealand and Sri Lanka are set to visit the country for long series each. Mohammad Shami & R Ashwin opened the bowling for the visitors and bowled brilliantly to stifle the batsmen. Ashwin removed Karunarane(16) early with a sharp offspinner that kissed the southpaw's outside edge before nestling in the hands of Rahane at slip. Shami bowled a dream spell of 6-3-15-2, troubling the batsmen with his subtle variations. He had nightwatchman Pushpakumara(1) caught behind with a terrific delivery and trapped Mendis(12) LBW with a straight delivery.  Captain Chandimal(26*) and former skipper Matthews(17*) dug deep and resisted the relentless Indian bowlers till Lunch. India lost a review after unsuccessfully appealing for a caught behind decision of Mathews.  The duo need to bat on and on for Sri Lanka to harbour any hope turning the tables on India. ðŸ“° *GB8*: *15-day window post IPL not possible till 2023: BCCI*  For fear of losing a sizeable sum if a 15-day gap between the Indian Premier League (IPL) and the domestic international calendar is implemented, the BCCI office-bearers have told the Committee of Administrators (CoA), in a recently-held meeting in the capital, that Justice (retired) RM Lodha panel's recommendation can't be honored till 2023. ðŸ“° *GB7*: *Under-19 Asia Cup moved out of India*  The Asian Cricket Council has withdrawn the hosting rights of the 2017 Under-19 Asia Cup from India and handed it over to Malaysia, following their annual general body meeting. A decision on the senior team Asia Cup, also scheduled to be held in India next year, however, has been deferred until the ACC's next meeting.  The PCB had raised its objections to touring India for the Under-19 Asia Cup, which was to be played in Bengaluru in November. Given the tense political climate between India and Pakistan, PCB chairman Najam Sethi, who also heads the ACC, tabled a resolution to get it shifted. The BCCI had already written to the Indian government, seeking clearance to host the event as it would include a team from Pakistan.  "The matter of shifting the tournament to Malaysia was amicably agreed by all participants in the development and executive committees, since no one wanted it marred by security considerations of any member," said Sethi. ðŸ“° *GC0*: *Sri Lanka 'keen' to visit Pakistan for T20s in September*  Pakistan could be on the verge of hosting their highest-profile international visitor in the last eight years, with Sri Lanka all but committing to play a T20 there in September or October. This would, in itself, represent an extraordinary gesture by SLC, given its own side had been the target of the 2009 terror attack that stopped international cricket being played in Pakistan for six years. Since that attack, in which six policemen and two civilians were killed, only Zimbabwe have toured the country, playing five internationals in Lahore in 2015.  Sri Lanka and Pakistan are due to play each other in a full series that starts at the end of September. An SLC release said that "Sri Lanka will play at least one of the three T20s in Lahore, in September," so long as "the logistical and operational plans fall in place". *IndiaðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ Bring a Swift Conclusionâ˜ to SL Innings*  ðŸ”°IND 487 beat SL 135 & 181 (Dickwella 41, Ashwin 4/68) by an innings and 171 runs  India completed their first ever clean sweep in an away series after completing an innings victory in the 3âƒ£rd Test against Sri Lanka at Pallekele.  SL started the day at 19/1 and were always expected to succumb to India but just like in the first innings, the end was swift. Mohammed Shami was brilliant up front, getting rid of Pushpakumara and Kusal Mendis early on to put up the writing on the wall for the Lankans.  However, there was a small partnership between Chandimal and Mathews that stopped India's charge till lunch. But in the second session, it unravelled fast for SL. The captain fell first, lobbing a catch to short-leg off Kuldeep Yadav before Ashwin trapped Mathews in front. Once the two mainstays went, it was all a case of when and not if.  Dickwella prolonged the end with a quickfire 41 but India kept chipping away and brought about a swift conclusion to the innings. It really has been an efficient performance from India. But one needs to understand that SL have offered extremely little in terms of fight.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397674634*  Type ðŸ‘GP6 to like this

Second on the list, Kohli still needed five more wins to achieve the top spot on the list, which has Sourav Ganguly leading with 11 wins. "We will honour and appreciate our top players and umpires in the same award ceremony to encourage them," he said. ðŸ“° *KV4*: *Don't take the Kolpak way: Donald pleads to Morkel*  Allan Donald, the former South Africa fast bowler, has made a public appeal, requesting Morne Morkel to not go the Kolpak route after reports emerged that the Titans fast bowler and Hashim Amla were considering their future.  "Don't reconsider your future. South Africa needs you. Your performances against England in the Test series were the best I have seen you bowl in a very, very long time," Donald was quoted as saying by Titans' official website.  "Give him what he wants. Let him retire on his terms. We need him this summer. I have not seen him bowl this well for many, many seasons. There's no doubt, Morkel is world-class. It is just a shame that he did not take bucket loads of wickets in England because he deserved it. He beat the bat on countless occasions without reward," he added.  A raft of South African players, including Stiaan van Zyl, Hardus Viljoen, Daryn Smit, Rilee Rossouw, Kyle Abbott, David Wiese, Simon Harmer and Dane Vilas have secured Kolpak deals with English counties in recent times. Marchant de Lange, the fast bowler, too, secured a contract (as a local player) with Glamorgan in March this year. ðŸ“° *LZ2*: *Umar Akmal furious at being denied NCA facilities*  Umar Akmal might have been out of the national side for a while, but he stormed back into the headlines on Wednesday with an explosive press conference in Lahore, with the target of his ire no less than head coach Mickey Arthur. Akmal alleged that Arthur used abusive language against him and barred him from using the National Cricket Academy, saying he had to 'earn that right'.  Akmal told reporters that he was 'insulted' by the head coach and deprived of the opportunity to "improve myself". The PCB instantly took note of his outburst, issuing a show-cause notice demanding he respond within a fortnight.  "I had gone to England for rehabilitation of my knee injury," Akmal said in a press conference on Wednesday. "After I recovered, I went to the NCA to start working on my fitness and training. But the coaching staff doesn't want to work with me at all. When I asked why all those international coaches didn't want to work with me, they responded that they wanted to prioritise working with players who had central contracts. I said that I too am an international Pakistan cricketer, and if my fitness is lacking - and I admit that along the way my fitness has been found wanting - they should help me.  "I then went to talk to the chief selector (Inzamam), but he referred me to Mickey Arthur. Arthur took me back to Inzi bhai's room and started scolding me and using bad language in front of Inzi bhai, which I found demeaning and insulting." ðŸ“° *LZ0*: *Kohli has lot of Australian spirit in him: Michael Clarke*  The Australian media and some of the current players may not waste any opportunity to criticize Virat Kohli, but Michael Clarke thinks highly of the the Indian captain.  The former Aussie captain feels the Indian batting stalwart is often misunderstood for his on-field antics, especially in Australia, but acknowledges that he also has enough number of fans Down Under.  "I disagree that Virat doesn't have too many fans in Australia. I think Virat has a lot of Australian spirit in him," said Clarke. "To be honest, he plays the game really tough and is really competitive on the field, but he is a nice guy off the field. So when people get to know Virat, they realize that what they see on the field is just his competitive spirit. I can't think of any Australian cricketer who wasn't like that every time we walked out on the field. I certainly think there is respect for Virat in Australia."  "You probably are not going to read the positive stuff (about Virat) in the Australian media though. They all want to write a negative story. But I have a great relation with him and I think he is respectful," he added. ðŸ“° *RS3*: *I Never Felt Anil Kumble Was Strict, Says Wriddhiman Saha*  Wriddhiman Saha said that he never felt that former India coach Anil Kumble was strict. Kumble had stepped down from the post of the top job due to differences of opinion with skipper Virat Kohli just after the ICC Champions Trophy.  Talking about the perception of Kumble being strict, Saha said, "I did not feel that way. As a coach, he had to be strict in some way or the other. Some have felt he is strict, some have not. I have never felt that way under Anil bhai," Saha told reporters on Friday.      Comparing Ravi Shastri's style of coaching with that of Kumble, the right-handed batsman said, "Anil bhai always wanted us to score big -- 400,500 and 600 and felt that the opponent can be bowled out within 150-200. That's not always possible."   "Ravi bhai, on the other hand, always tells us to go for the kill. Go out there and hit the opponent out of the park. This is the only difference I could see. Rest, both spoke positive stuff." ðŸ“° *RS6*: *Tests or ODIs, Michael Clarke feels India are always tough to beat at home*  Michael Clarke visits India more often now than he did during his playing days as an Australia cricketer. But significantly, the former Aussie captain has perfected the art of ducking under the bouncer with the microphone in hand.  Asked if if Australia had it in them to beat India on turning tracks, next month. Smothering the spin of the question, he replied, "ODI cricket is a lot different from Test cricket, so I would imagine the wickets would be very good. I think we will see some entertaining cricket. Hopefully, the Aussies can perform well and win. But it is going to be tough. India is always good in their backyard." *Cook, Root shine on pink-ball's England premiereðŸ“¹* http://v.duta.us/SBuAlAAA  Day 1 - Stumps  England 348 for 3 (Cook 153*, Root 136) v West Indies  On the occasion of the very first day-night Test in England, hundreds for both Alastair Cook and Joe Root put the hosts firmly in command at Edgbaston against Windies. On as flat a Test pitch as you are likely to find, and with the sun shining for most of the day, England finished on 348 for 3 as the tourists' bowlers struggled to maintain consistency and control. It already looks a long way back for them.  HighlightsðŸ“¹http://v.duta.us/SBuAlAAA  Cook and Root showed all their class during a partnership of 248 after debutant Mark Stoneman, who had been presented with his first Test cap by Jonathan Trott before play, and Tom Westley had been dismissed within the first eight overs. There were a few plays and misses and a couple of edges through the slip cordon from Root and Cook but England's two best batsmen were largely untroubled. ðŸ“° *VK9*: *Kohli Hints At Chahal, Kuldeep Inclusion in First ODI*  India captain Virat Kohli on Saturday hinted at playing left-arm wrist (chinaman) spinner Kuldeep Yadav and leg-spinner Yuzvendra Chahal in the first One-Day International (ODI) cricket match against Sri Lanka at the Rangiri Dambulla International Stadium here on Sunday.  Left-arm spinner Axar Patel, Kuldeep and Yuzvendra are captain Kohli's options among slow bowlers in the five-match series for India, who have rested spin-twins Ravichandran Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja.  "I see only two guys (spinners) taking the field. Now who are going to be those guys it really depends you know what we feel like going in as a team. But see having wrist spinners in the team is always an advantage you see teams across the world they at least have one wrist spinner if not two helping their side giving important breakthroughs," Kohli told reporters.  The 28-year-old also revealed India will opt to play three regular seamers with Hardik Pandya as the third option.  "I don't see this pitch having three spinners, we have played here in the past it's probably three fast bowlers kind of a pitch which Hardik Pandya does for us as the third seamer, is good enough to give 7-8 overs," the right-handed batsman said.  Kohli also mentioned that Kedar Jadhav, K.L Rahul and Manish Pandey will have to compete for two spots in the playing XI. ðŸ“° *VL0*: *Stuart Broad overtakes Sir Ian Botham in England's Test wicket taking list*  Stuart Broad lent a famous hand as England took a remarkable 19 wickets on day three of this country's inaugural floodlit Test to inflict a crushing innings-and-209-run defeat on hapless West Indies at Edgbaston.  Only Jermaine Blackwood (79 not out) provided any resistance in a first-innings 168 all out, and not even he could hold up the England juggernaut on its second run as Broad moved into overdrive to surpass the great Sir Ian Botham and take second place behind his team-mate James Anderson in the national all-time list of Test wicket-takers.  Soon afterwards, the tourists had folded for 137 to go 1-0 down in double-quick time with two more to play in this Investec series.
