*Red Hot DhawanðŸ’¥ Burns Sorry Sri LankaðŸ”¥*  By ShadowfaxðŸŽ  ðŸ”° SL 216 (Dickwella 64, Axar 3/34) lost to IND 220/1 (Dhawan 132*, Kohli 82*) by 9 wickets  Even the diehard fans of Sri Lanka would not have expected them to beat India in the first ODI at Dambulla on Sunday, given the whipping they received in the Test series. But the authoritative manner in which Sri Lanka were dismissed in the game by India would have been a surprise for them.  A comprehensive 9-wicket win, with 127 balls remaining, only served to highlight the difference in gulf between the two teams and take more sheen off a series that has been criminally lopsided so far.  Having been inserted to bat, Sri Lanka started well enough with Dickwella (64), Gunathilaka (35) and Mendis (36) powering them forward. However, the Indian spinners halted their progress and struck vital blows, especially Kedar Jadhav who has gained reputation as a partnership-breaker. SL went on to commit harakiri and plunged to 216 all out from 150/2.  India's chase can only be described as 'whirlwind'. Rohit was run out in an unfortunate manner but Shikhar Dhawan (132*) was in a punitive mood and raced to a 70-ball 100, along with a busy Kohli (82*). They treated the bowlers with absolute disdain once they saw none of them had the skill or purpose to test them.  The comprehensive win can only be termed a 'hammering'.  â­MoM: Shikhar Dhawan  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397680554*  Type ðŸ‘WD9 to like this

ðŸ“° *WF9*: *Cook surges up batting rankings after double-ton*  England opener Alistair Cook has made a strong charge on the ICC rankings for Test batsmen following a stellar performance in the day/night Test against the West Indies, which the hosts won by an innings and 209 runs at Edgbaston on Saturday.  Cook not only walked away with the man of the match award for his 243 i the first innings, but his fourth career double-century also earned him six points that has put him in sixth spot in the latest rankings.  This is former England skipper Cook's highest ranking since he surged to number five in March 2013.  Cook, who achieved a career-high second place in September 2011, now has India captain Virat Kohli firmly within his sights as the England opener is just eight points behind the India captain.  England captain Joe Root has returned to the 900-point mark following his 13th career century.  For scoring 136, Root received 14 points, which has taken him to 905 points â€“ 36 behind Australia captain Steve Smith, who will defend his number-one ranking in the upcoming two-Test series against Bangladesh. ðŸ“° *XW9*: *Sri Lanka fans hold up team bus to express displeasure*  A section of Sri Lanka spectators held up the team bus and voiced raucous displeasure at the performance of players and administration following the nine-wicket loss against India in Dambulla.  A group of about 50 fans had stood in the vicinity of Sri Lanka's parked bus, hooting and shouting slogans such as "we want our cricket back" and "no politics in cricket", until police stepped in and cleared the gathering. The incident had delayed Sri Lanka's departure from the venue by close to half an hour.  After the incident, Sri Lankan legend Kumar Sangakkara tweeted, ""When we won, you celebrated with us, and when we lost, you grieved alongside us," he said. "When the team was struggling - when we were most in need - your love and support was our strength. Now, what our cricketers need is that same, love, support, patience and effort. Let's hope for the team's victory, and support them as one." ðŸ“° *XX2*: *Curtly Ambrose slams 'pathetic' West Indies*  Curtly Ambrose labelled the current West Indies side "embarrassing" and "pathetic" after their humiliating innings defeat by England in the first Test.      West Indies lost 19 wickets in under a day on Saturday after being made to follow-on.   "In the end it was totally embarrassing," West Indies fast-bowling great Ambrose said. "I never saw any aggression from the West Indies players throughout the three days. There was no belief that they could compete, let alone beat England. They seemed to be waiting for England to make mistakes and at this level that is not going to work. Trust me, it was painful to watch."      West Indies have now won just three out of 87 away Tests in the past 20 years excluding matches against Bangladesh and Zimbabwe.      Ambrose said he had tried to stop the slide as a member of the backroom staff but in the end felt it was a "waste of time". *ðŸ’¥ AB De Villiersâ­ Steps Down as ODI Captain*  AB de Villiers announced that he has stepped down as South Africa's ODI captain. As a player, he has made himself available for all 3 formats from October onwards following discussions with CSA.  "Faf du Plessis has proved to be an outstanding captain of the T20 and Test teams, and bearing this in mind, I have informed Cricket South Africa that I would like to step down as captain of the ODI team," de Villiers said. "It has been an honour to lead the team for the past six years, but it is now time for someone else to take the ODI side forward. Whoever is chosen as the new ODI captain will have my complete support."  "Following this recent break, I really do feel refreshed and revived. I want to get back on the field and I have today assured the national selectors that I will be available for selection in all three formats of the game during the coming season. There is plenty of hard work ahead in the nets and I must prepare properly, but I will be ready to play, if required, from the middle of October onwards."  ABD will not be back in time for the Test series against Bangladesh which begins at the end of September. However, he is expected to mark his comeback in Tests against India in December or early next year.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397687598*  Type ðŸ‘DW0 to like this

ðŸ“° *FF0*: *Compassionate Kohli Understands Sri Lanka's Troubled Transition*  Retirements of well-established players always leave a team in a state of limbo. Building for the future while also trying to handle the current task at hand can turn out to be tiresome, as Sri Lanka are experiencing right now.  Ahead of the 2nd ODI against Sri Lanka, when Indian captain Virat Kohli was asked about Sri Lanka's current state he drew parallels with what India experienced a few years back when their greats decided to call it quits.  "It is difficult for any team going through transition. One thing that we decided to do as a team was take more responsibility and ownership of what we do on the field, playing for the country. We just needed to change our mindset," reminisced Kohli. "It didn't matter if we were playing against a side that has played 60 Tests each, if we are mentally more prepared than them then we are in a better position to win. So we decided to put our heads in that zone where experience didn't matter much for us. It was the fight and competitiveness we were willing to show and the desire to fight for longer periods that helped us get through that phase quicker than what others might have faced." *SLðŸ†šIND: Sri LankaðŸ‡±ðŸ‡° Labour to 236*  Toss - India  Sri Lanka - 236/8 (50/50 ov)  (Siriwardana 58, Kapugedara 40; Bumrah 4-43 )  Virat Kohli won the toss for the 5th consecutive time this tour and predictably opted to chase in the 2nd ODI at Kandy.  Sri Lanka got off to a flier with hardhitting Niroshan Dickwella making good use of the powerplay. However, like in the first game, the hosts were unable to sustain their momentum. Jasprith Bumrah ended Dickwella's(31) promising innings with a slower ball that resulted in the southpaw chipping a catch to midwicket.  Indian spinners bowled admirably in the middle overs and put the brakes on the scoring rate. Leg-spinner Yuzhvendra Chahal picked up the wickets of Gunathilaka & Mendis to finish with figures of 2-42 while Axar Patel had figures of 1-30.  Sri Lanka were tottering at 121/5 in the 29th over and it looked like another meek surrender was on the cards. However, a dogged partnership of 91 runs between Siriwardana & Kapugedera revived their innings. Siriwardana provided the impetus, scoring a run-a-ball fifty while Kapugedara took a while to get his eye in.     India pulled things back in the final few overs and the hosts finished at 236/8. Though it is a commendable recovery by the hosts, it doesn't pose a challenge for their in-form opponents. Sri Lanka need an at least an inspired bowling performance if not a miracle to stop Kohli & co. from achieving this target.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919840848931*  Type ðŸ‘GG2 to like this

ðŸ“° *GH8*: *Former Women's Captain Labels BCCI a 'Male Chauvinist Organisation'*  India women's team's first ever ODI skipper , Diana Edulji, had some choice words to say about the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) and its attitude towards women's cricket at an event. She called the BCCI a "male chauvinist organisation". She also claimed that the women's cricket team's spectacular performance at the World Cup final in England last month had been difficult to stomach for many members in the sexist organisation.  She was appointed to a four-member Committee of Administrators (CoA) for the BCCI by the Supreme Court (SC) in January this year.  "I've always been a BCCI basher, right from the day women's cricket came into the BCCI fold in 2006... They never wanted women to dictate terms or get into this thing," she said. In July, even though the Indian team lost the World Cup final to England by nine runs, they came back home to unprecedented publicity and love from fans who were finally sitting up and taking note of their stellar performance.  She also criticised former BCCI president N Srinivasan at the event. She claimed that he "hates women's cricket," and that when she went to congratulate him on his appointment in 2011 at Wankhede Stadium in Mumbai, he told her that if he could have it his way, he would "not let women's cricket happen". Ind 231/7 44.2 Ov Sl 236/8 50.0 Ov Dhoni 45(68), Bhuvneshwar 53(80) India has won the match.
India have been saved by a miraculous rescue act from MS Dhoni and Bhuvneshwar Kumar in Kandy after the middle order crumbled like a tea cake. With this victory, India are 2-0 up in the series.

Cangratulations!
*Miraculous WinâœŒ for India as DhoniðŸ˜Ž & Bhuvi Pull Off Sensational RescueðŸ™*  By ShadowfaxðŸŽ  ðŸ”° Sri Lanka 236 for 8 (Siriwardana 58, Bumrah 4-43) lost to India 231/7 (Rohit 54, Bhuvi 53*, Dananjaya 6/54)  It was a game India should have won easily when SL posted a mere 236 on the board after batting first. However, in the end, after sliding to 131/7 at one point in the chase, India should never have won it. But MS Dhoni, the wily old fox that he is, found an able ally in Bhuvneshwar Kumar and pulled off a rescue act of the highest order to send India 2-0 up in the 5 match series.  Sri Lanka themselves were in trouble in their innings after capitulating to 121/5, with Bumrah and the Indian spinners bowling brilliantly. However, Chamara Kapugedara (40) and Milinda Siriwardana (58) showed enterprise to ensure the Sri Lankan innings reached 236/8 at the end of 50 overs.  A rain delay meant that India had to chase only 231 in 47 overs and the chase got off to a rollicking start with Rohit Sharma (54) and Shikhar Dhawan (49) cutting loose in merciless fashion. India were 109/0 in 15.2 overs before Akila Dananjaya (6/54) spilt the seeds of chaos among the Indians with his impeccable googlies. Rohit went first, missing a sweep, before Dhawan top-edged a sweep of Siriwardana.  The only explanation for what followed was that the celebrated Indian batsmen were in a trance. Virat Kohli, KL Rahul, Kedar Jadhav, Hardik Pandya and Axar Patel were all flummoxed by Dananjaya's googlies as India slipped to 131/7 in a matter of a few overs.  When it looked as though India's end was near, Bhuvneshwar Kumar (53*) and MS Dhoni (40) showed the rest of the batsmen how to apply themselves and got India to their target without much fuss.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043013149*  Type ðŸ‘HF0 to like this

IA0
ðŸ“° *IA0*: *BCCI accepts Virender Sehwag's suggestion; remodels Ranji Trophy format*  The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) has remodelled the Ranji Trophy format for the upcoming season with the teams being divided into four groups with seven teams each.  By replacing the earlier format, which had three groups of nine teams each, the BCCI has ensured that the teams will play two games less at the group stage, thereby reducing the burden somewhat for the players, especially the fast bowlers.  The board also accepted Virender Sehwag's proposal to maintain at least a four-day gap between matches.  "Seven teams in each group will balance the tournament nicely. Most importantly, this format will help us manage the workload of the bowlers, particularly the pacers, in a better way. Keeping Sehwag's suggestion in mind, this time we've consciously kept a four-day gap between all games in the Ranji Trophy.  "This will help the bowlers recover well for the next game. Earlier, a bowler from a Ranji-winning team would end up bowling in 12 games within a few months. That workload has been reduced by two games," said a source in the Board. ðŸ“° *IA1*: *Sehwag, Gayle and Afridi to play in UAE T10 League*  Virender Sehwag, Chris Gayle, Shahid Afridi and Kumar Sangakkara will be part of the T10 league, named Ten Cricket League, in the United Arab Emirates (UAE).   Teams playing in the league are - Team Punjabis, Team Pakhtoons, Team Maratha, Team Banglas, Team Lankans, Team Sindhis and Team Keralites, among others.   Afridi will lead Team Pakhtoons. Habib Khan, owner of Pakhtoons commented: â€œI am excited to have Shahid Afridi, one of the greatest cricketers ever, to lead my team and you will see Pakhtoons in full force.â€  The league will have 10-over-a-side match with 90 minutes of action, spread over four days. The event will begin on December 21 and culminate on December 24 at the Sharjah Cricket Stadium.  Shaji ul Mulk, president of TCL, said: â€œWe are very excited about the concept of T10 as it brings cricket to the level of world sports of 90 minutes and fast pace action. We all enjoy T20. Wait till you experience T10!" ðŸ“° *JL5*: *Pakistan squad named for World XI series*  Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) has announced 16-member squad for three T20 Internationals against ICC World XI, which will take place in Lahore next month.  Pakistan have been trying to bring international cricket back to the country. As a process of it, Pakistan will host ICC World XI for three T20Is on September 12, 13 and 15.  A day after the announcement of World XI squad, Pakistan squad has also been named which includes 16 players. Umar Amin, Faheem Ashraf, Amir Yamin, Mohammad Amir, Sohail Khan, who werenâ€™t in the T20Is against West Indies, have been picked in the squad.  The World XI will be led by South Africa captain Faf du Plessis. Tamim Iqbal is also a part of the squad as the only Bangladeshi.  :beginenr:Pakistan squad: Sarfraz Ahmed (capt & wk), Fakhar Zaman, Ahmed Shehzad, Babar Azam, Shoaib Malik, Umar Amin, Imad Wasim, Shadab Khan, Mohammad Nawaz, Faheem Ashraf, Hasan Ali, Aamer Yamin, Mohammad Amir, Ruman Raees, Usman Khan, Sohail Khan  ðŸ”°World XI squad: Faf du Plessis (capt), Hashim Amla, Samuel Badree, George Bailey, Paul Collingwood, Ben Cutting, Grant Elliott, Tamim Iqbal, David Miller, Morne Morkel, Tim Paine, Thisara Perera, Imran Tahir, Darren Sammy  Read more: http://v.duta.us/fwahvgAA  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917550042562*  Type ðŸ‘JL5 to like this  *Collect ðŸ“¯ DUTA ðŸ“¯  Points ðŸ’°* You have *41 duta points* and are at level *ðŸ™‡â€â™€ï¸Apprentice*. ðŸ“° *JL6*: *Sri Lanka skipper Tharanga gets two-match suspension*  Sri Lanka skipper Upul Tharanga was given a two-match suspension for his team's slow over rate in the second one-day international against India in Pallekele on Thursday, the International Cricket Council said.  Tharanga will miss the next two matches of the five-match series, in Pallekele on Aug 27 and Colombo on Aug 31, after Sri Lanka were adjudged to have bowled three overs short of their target in the specified time.  It's the second time Tharanga has been suspended this year, after missing two matches in June's ICC Champions Trophy for the same offence of his side's slow over rate.  Sri Lanka brought in Dinesh Chandimal and Lahiru Thirimanne to the squad in place of opening batsman Danusha Gunathilaka and the suspended Tharanga. ðŸ“° *KL0*: *Lorgat hopes Indians will be part of Global T20 League one day*  The Indian cricket board's decision not to play the Boxing Day Test on its upcoming tour of South Africa has left the CSA disappointed, but there are no hard feelings, says board CEO Haroon Lorgat.  The Boxing Day Test begins on December 26, a day after Christmas. Now that it's not happening, the CSA wants to move on.  "We are disappointed that India won't be playing the Boxing Day Test because of their own tight schedule which is going into the far end of December by the time the Sri Lankan home series gets over."  "I believe BCCI too has it's own challenges as far as scheduling is concerned. We have been working for last 18 months and waiting for confirmation from the Indian board," Lorgat said during a chat with journalists on Friday (August 25), ahead of the inaugural T20 Global League's players' draft.  Lorgat, however, said that it would be great if some Indian T20 specialists could take take part in the Global T20 league, which is due to be played in IPL style with eight teams and 57 games.  "We are happy that all top T20 players from different countries are going to take part in the tournaments. If the Indians walk into this league, it would be good for world." ðŸ“° *JL6*: *Sri Lanka skipper Tharanga gets two-match suspension*  Sri Lanka skipper Upul Tharanga was given a two-match suspension for his team's slow over rate in the second one-day international against India in Pallekele on Thursday, the International Cricket Council said.  Tharanga will miss the next two matches of the five-match series, in Pallekele on Aug 27 and Colombo on Aug 31, after Sri Lanka were adjudged to have bowled three overs short of their target in the specified time.  It's the second time Tharanga has been suspended this year, after missing two matches in June's ICC Champions Trophy for the same offence of his side's slow over rate.  Sri Lanka brought in Dinesh Chandimal and Lahiru Thirimanne to the squad in place of opening batsman Danusha Gunathilaka and the suspended Tharanga. ðŸ“° *OG9*: *Brathwaite, Hope punish England as Windies flourish*  ðŸ”° West Indies 329 for 5 (S Hope 147*, Blackwood 21*) lead England 258 by 71 runs  Opener Kraigg Brathwaite carved out his sixth Test hundred while immensely talented stroke-maker Shai Hope gathered his first, as West Indies dominated England to take a surprise advantage on the second day of the second Test at Headingley here Saturday.  Under heavy criticism following a heavy innings defeat inside three days last weekend, the Caribbean side responded strongly by piling up 329 for five in their first innings at the close â€“ a lead of 71 heading into Sundayâ€™s third day.  At the heart of the Windies' enterprise were Brathwaite and Hope who combined prudence and aggression to subdue Englandâ€™s much-vaunted seam attack.  Hope was unbeaten on 147 at the close, an innings that has so far consumed six hours flat and lasted 252 balls, with 23 boundaries. The knock was also the highest individual score by a West Indies batsman in a Test in England in 22 years.  He was partnered by Jermaine Blackwood who has already stroked four boundaries in a 23-ball 21.  Brathwaite, meanwhile, gathered 134 â€“ a knock that included 17 fours and two sixes, and came from 249 deliveries in six hours and 20 minutes at the crease. Sri Lanka have the sole aim of keeping the 5-game series alive when they take on India at Pallekele in the 3rd ODI, having lost the first two games. What's interesting is the fact that they have lost the services of their leader Upul Tharanga who has been banned for slow over rate. Chamara Kapugedara will lead the team in his absence.   The Lankans have brought back Dinesh Chandimal and Lahiru Thirimanne for the remaining games of the series as they look for a bit of inspiration to build on Akila Dananjaya's devastating performance in the last ODI. The tweaker picked up six Indian wickets and almost won the game for SL single handedly. But MS Dhoni and Bhuvneshwar Kumar showed grit to win the game for India, who will be wary of Dananjaya this time.   India will be eager to ensure their middle over gets to bat a lot, given that their top order has been firing a lot. India might be expected to shuffle their batting order again to ensure everybody gets time out in the middle. India have made no changes from their last game.

*Ro'Hit' SwatsðŸ’¥ Away Sorry Lankans to Seal SeriesðŸŽ‰*  By ShadowfaxðŸŽ  ðŸ”° Sri Lanka 217 for 9 (Thirimanne 80, Bumrah 5-27) lost to India 218/4 (R Sharma 124*, MS Dhoni 67*)  India have sealed the five-match ODI series against Sri Lanka by surging to an unassailable 3-0 lead at Pallekel tonight, on the back of a composed ton by Rohit Sharma.  India, who were asked to bowl first, came up with a controlled performance, led by Jasprit Bumrah, and never allowed the Lankan innings to get out of hand. Bumrah made two early breakthroughs before Chindimal and Thirimanne stitched a partnership together. However, Pandya got rid of the former before Mathews fell to Jadhav. From then on, it was all downhill for SL with Bumrah rampaging through the tail to pick up a five-wicket haul as they were restricted to a mere 217/9.  In reply, India's chase did not get off to the best of starts. Dhawan played on to Malinga before Kohli's flick found fine leg. Though Rahul stayed for a bit alongside Rohit, he lost the plot once Dananjaya, India's tormentor in the previous game, came on. Rahul found deep midwicket with a full before Kedar Jadhav was bamboozled for the second etime running. But Dhoni and Rohit gathered themselves and batted sensibly to ensure there was not another collapse.  Rohit soon asserted himself and sped away to his 12th ODI hundred while Dhoni brought about his half-century with an imperious swat over point. Though the game had to be stopped for a bit at the end because of crowd trouble, it only delayed the inevitable.  â­MoM: Jasprit Bumrah  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +919043008093*  Type ðŸ‘QU6 to like this

*Shakib Inspires ðŸ‡§ðŸ‡©B'desh's 1âƒ£ Ever Win Over AUSðŸ‡¦ðŸ‡º*  ðŸ”° Bangladesh 260 & 221: Tamim 78, Mushfiqur 41; Lyon 6-82 beat Australia 217 & 244: Warner 112; Shakib 5-85 by 20 runs  Steven Smith became the first Australian captain to preside over a Test defeat to the Tigers, ranked a lowly ninth in the game's longest format.  Set a challenging 265 to win for what would have been their second highest successful fourth innings run chase in the subcontinent, the tourists were nearing the home straight after Smith and his deputy David Warner added 49 to Australia's overnight total of 2-109.  The pair had put on 130, with Warner posting a brilliant ton, his first Test century overseas since late in 2014, and just his second Test ton in Asia. But the contest swung when the opener was struck on the pad in line with middle stump by Shakib Al Hasan on 112.  Smith and new batsman Peter Handscomb advanced the score to 3-170 at drinks, but the skipper faintly edged an angling ball from Shakib to be sharply caught behind the stumps. Handscomb was removed for just 15 after cutting spinner Taijul Islam to Soumya Sarkar at first slip.  A kill was there for the taking, and it looked likely to eventuate when Matthew Wade again departed cheaply LBW, prompting a jubilant dance from bowler Shakib. Ashton Agar then fell for just two after spooning a return catch to Taijul.  It was clear there would be no comeback though when Maxwell was bowled for 14 with the first ball after lunch, giving Shakib 10 wickets for the match to go with his first innings knock of 84. While some lusty late hitting from Cummins boosted hopes of a miraculous revival, Hazlewood was eventually trapped by Taijul for a duck, leading to pandemonium in the stands. Kj7
ðŸ“° *KJ7*: *Angola elections: Ruling MPLA wins parliamentary vote*  Angola's ruling MPLA party has won the country's parliamentary elections, but lost ground to the opposition, the electoral commission said citing provisional results.  Joao Lourenco, the country's defence minister, will replace President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, who is stepping down after 38 years in power.  The 74-year-old dos Santos is expected to remain head of the ruling People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola (MPLA) party, which has ruled Angola since it gained independence from Portuguese rule in 1975.  The electoral commission said the MPLA had won 150 of 220 parliamentary seats in the National Assembly, giving them the two-thirds majority needed to pass any legislation without help from another party.  "The process violated the law and the principles of democracy," Claudio Silva, who sits on the electoral commission as a UNITA representative, told Reuters news agency. Malinga OUT b Kuldeep Yadav ðŸŽ³ 0(1) 0x6 0x4 Sl 207/10 42.4 Ov Ind 375/5 50.0 Ov Dananjaya 11(19)
Sl 207/10 42.4 Ov Ind 375/5 50.0 Ov Dananjaya 11(19) India has won the match.
Kuldeep deceived Fernando in flight. The tail-ender looks for a big drive but could only hit it back off a thick inside edge for a simple return catch.
Kuldeep dismisses Malinga off the very next ball. Big turner spins past Malinga's swipe and crashes into the stumps to seal another emphatic win for Kohli's men
This is Sri Lanka's biggest defeat at home in terms of runs(178).
India 375/5 (Kohli 132, Rohit Sharma 104; Mathews 2-24) beat Sri Lanka 207(Mathews 70; Kuldeep 2/31, Bumrah 2-32) by 168 runs  India thumped Sri Lanka yet again, in the 4th ODI of the series. Twin centuries from Virat Kohli & Rohit Sharma helped the visitors post a mammoth total of 375/5.   Sri Lanka's approach in chasing down the huge total lacked direction as they lost wickets at regular intervals. Angelo Matthews delayed the inevitable defeat with a patient half-century but his team-mates couldn't lend support to help their team's cause. India handed a debut to young pacer Shardhul Thakur who finished with figures of 1-26 in his 7 overs. Kuldeep Yadav, Jasprith Bumrah & Hardik Pandya picked up two wickets each.  The two teams will meet for the final ODI on Sunday at the same venue.

ðŸ“° *CU4*: *Malinga to assess future after current series*  Sri Lankan paceman Lasith Malinga says that he will assess his future after the current series against India. Malinga, who turned 34 on Monday, captained Sri Lanka in the absence of suspended captain Upul Tharanga in the fourth One-Day International on Thursday (August 31) at the R. Premadasa Stadium in Colombo and went onto complete 300 one-day wickets when he dismissed Indian captain Virat Kohli.  "I'm playing after 19 months following a leg injury," said Malinga. "In the Zimbabwe and India series I couldn't play well. I'll see where I'm at after this series, and evaluate how long I can play given the way my body is.  "No matter how experienced I am, if I can't win a match for the team and do what the team needs, there's no point in me being here. I'll see if I can make up for that 19 months and regain that form over the next three or four months." ðŸ“° *IW2*: *Virat Kohli and India eye whitewash against Sri Lanka in 5th ODI*  A rampaging India will fancy their chances of completing a 5-0 whitewash of Sri Lanka when they face the beleaguered hosts in the fifth and final ODI here today. Virat Kohli & Co. already swept the Test series 3-0, and given their dominant run on this trip, would like to sweep the ODI series as well.  Sri Lanka are in danger of losing a second successive ODI series to India by a 5-0 margin. The last time these two sides played a bilateral series in November 2014, a depleted Lankan side lost 5-0 in India.  Their fortunes havenâ€™t changed much since and another loss would be a serious body blow for the hosts in what has been a traumatic summer of cricket. They have already foregone the opportunity to automatically qualify for the 2019 ODI World Cup by failing to win two matches in this series. *SLðŸ†šIND 5th ODI: Bhuviâš¡ Picks 5âƒ£, MSDðŸ˜Ž 100 & SL - 238â€¼*  Sri Lanka - 238 in 49.4(Thirimanne 67(102), Mathews 55(98), Tharanga 48(34) ; Bhuvaneshwar Kumar 5-42, Bumrah 2-45)  India have been set a modest target of 239 by Sri Lanka after the hosts won the toss for only the 2nd time in this tour and opted to bat. India now have a golden opportunity to complete their 2nd ever overseas whitewash.      Upul Tharanga returned to captain the team. His aggressive batting up front provided impetus but didn't last long. Indian pacers Bhuvi & Bumrah chipped away at the top order and reduced the opponents to 63/3 by the 10th over. Thirimanne & Matthews joined forces to buckle down and build the innings. Both the batsmen played as though they were trying to save a Test on a 5th-day pitch. Though they prevented a collapse the pair also drained any momentum the innings previously had. Having consumed as many deliveries as they did both the batsmen couldn't bat till the end and fell just before the slog overs. Virat Kohli experimented with his wrist spinners at the death and they were effective against the mediocre Sri Lankan lower order. MS Dhoni achieved a personal milestone when he stumped Dhananjeya off the bowling of Chahal. He became the 1st ODI keeper to complete 100 stumpings.  Bhuvaneshwar Kumar helped himself to his career best bowling figures. His bowling was accurate and was difficult to put away for the Lankans.     Maybe Sometimes cricket is about small victories. Sri Lanka won the toss. Lasted fifty overs, well almost. Two batsmen scored half-centuries. There wasn't any crowd trouble.  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917845093969*  Type ðŸ‘JQ7 to like this

*Kohli-led INDðŸ‡®ðŸ‡³ Thrash Hapless SLðŸ‡±ðŸ‡° to Complete WhitewashðŸ’¥*  ðŸ”° Sri Lanka 238 (Thirimanne 67, Bhuvneshwar 5-42) lost to India 239/4 (Kohli 110*, Jadhav 63, de Silva 1/29)  India have completed a thoroughly dominant tour in Sri Lanka by whitewashing the home team in the 5âƒ£-game ODI series, to add to the Test series whitewash earlier.  A hapless Sri Lankans were never a match for India, apart from several moments which were few and far between to really matter. In the final game on Sunday, Sri Lanka batted first but were jolted early on by the loss of Dickwella and Munaweera, both of whom were prised out by Bhuvneshwar Kumar. Captain Tharanga (48) who was in an aggressive mood also fell to Bumrah before Mathews (55) and Thirimanne (67) put together a good stand. But from a promising position of 185/3, they collapsed to 238 all out with Bhuvneshwar Kumar completing a five-wicket haul.  India's chase did not really get off to a good start with Rahane top-edging a pull off Malinga before Rohit's attempted scoop found a leaping Pushpakumara at short fine leg. But Manish Pandey (36) gave a free-scoring Virat Kohli (110*) the company he needed to steady the ship and then power it forward. Though Pandey fell in between, Kedar Jadhav (63) made the most of his chance with a fluent half-century to help Kohli notch his 30th ODI ton and make a mockery of the chase and the series.  â­MoM: Bhuvneshwar Kumar  ðŸŒŸMan of the Series: Jasprit Bumrah  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397687115*  Type ðŸ‘KC7 to like this

*ðŸ“ºStar WinsðŸŽ‰ IPL Rights for $2.55 BillionðŸ’°*  The BCCI has bagged INR 16,347.5 crore (US$ 2.55 billion) for its IPL television and digital rights from a single bidder, Star India, which made a consolidated offer for rights worldwide. The rights are for a 5-year period from 2018 to 2022.  A total of 24 companies had bought the tender document but only 14 made bids. There were 7 categories:    ðŸ“ºTelevision in India    ðŸ“±Digital in India    âœˆRights for the USA, Europe, Middle East, Africa and the rest of the world  For the 5 international markets, the bids included both television and digital rights. Star won them all by making one consolidated bid (INR 16,347.5 crore) - the only bidder to do so - that was larger than the sum of all the highest bids for each category (INR 15,819.51 crore). *Stokes, Moeen rested for one-off T20I against Windies*  England have resisted the temptation to rest players for the upcoming five-match One-Day International series against Windies. It had been thought they would rest some of their multi-format players ahead of the winter's Ashes tour but Joe Root, Moeen Ali, Ben Stokes, Chris Woakes and Jonny Bairstow have all been included in the ODI squad although Moeen, Woakes and Stokes will be rested for the solitary T20 match at Durham next Saturday (September 16).  T20I Squad: Eoin Morgan (c), Jonny Bairstow, Jake Ball, Jos Buttler (wk), Tom Curran , Liam Dawson, Alex Hales, Chris Jordan, Dawid Malan, Liam Plunkett, Adil Rashid, Joe Root, Jason Roy, David Willey. *Tharanga opts out of Test cricket for six months*  Sri Lanka's limited-overs captain Upul Tharanga has opted out of Test cricket for six months in order to focus on the white-ball formats. The outgoing selectors, headed by Sanath Jayasuriya, did not name Tharanga among the 25 in the provisional Test squad for the forthcoming games against Pakistan in the UAE.  Tharanga has been modest in Tests this year with 430 runs from eight matches, but has been successful in ODIs with an average of 47.21 - even as he has presided over two 0-5 whitewashes at the hands of India and South Africa.  The squad is expected to be trimmed to 15 by the next set of selectors, who are yet to be named. *Three SA-born cricketers named in Netherlandsâ€™ squad for ICC matches*  Two former South African first-class cricketers and an ex-Proteas player have been named in the Netherlandsâ€™ squad for next monthâ€™s International Cricket Council (ICC) World Cricket League Championship fixtures against Kenya.  Batsman Stephan Myburgh, who played for Northerns, and wrist spinner Michael Rippon, who represented the Cape Cobras, will join all-rounder Roelof van der Merwe in the 14-man party for key fixtures in Nairobi on October 6 and 8.  Van der Merwe gathered 13 ODIs for South Africa before switching allegiance and has since played 11 Twenty20 Internationals for the Dutch. ;IND - 174/3 (Kohli 82, Pandey 51*) bt SL - 170/7 (Munaveera 53; Chahal 3-43, Kuldeep 2-20) by 7 wickets    Ruthless Virat Kohlli led from the front to ensure that his team won all games in all formats in this tour. Chasing 171, India romped home with 7 wickets to spare.  At the end of the games the score reads, SL 0-9 IND  Sri Lanka, who have looked hapless in the past couple of months, mustered some grit for the last day of the tour to put up a decent batting performance. The T20 format helped their cause as their batsmen came out swinging. Munaweera scored quickfire half-century and provided a good start for the hosts. The 3 Indian spinners (Kuldeep, Chahal & Axar) picked up 5 wickets between them and put the brakes on the scoring. Sri Lanka recovered well after a slump in the middle overs, thanks to Priyanjan's run-a-ball 40 which prevented a collapse and helped them along to post 170/7.   In their chase, India lost Rohit Sharma(9) early. KL Rahul(24) looked in good nick but his innings was cut short by a superb catch at cover by Shanaka. From then on, Kohli took control of the chase and took the game away from the Lankans. The all familiar calculated aggression from the Indian captain brought the opponents to their knees. Kohli ran hard between the wickets, his timing was impeccable and he found the boundary ropes at will.  . Manish Pandey made the most of his opportunity and played a gem of an innings at the other end. The duo forged a 119-run partnership for the 3rd wicket and took India within touching distance of victory. Kohli holed out at deep midwicket with a few runs to go but the visitors got over the line in the final over.

*ICC Test Rankings: India Maintain Stranglehold On Top Spot, Australia Slip*  India continued to top the ICC Test rankings after whitewashing Sri Lanka 3-0 in the recently concluded Test series.  However, Australia, who drew the on-going series 1-1 with Bangladesh, slipped one rung to 5th in the latest list released on Thursday.      India, who swept the Sri Lanka have 125 points. On the other hand, Australia are now on 97 points, the same as New Zealand, but are behind on decimal points. In the three Tests against Sri Lanka, India thumped the hosts by 304 runs, an innings and 53 runs and an innings and 171 runs respectively.  Test Ratings:   1.India - 125   2.South Africa - 110   3.England - 105   4.New Zealand - 97   5.Australia - 97   6.Pakistan - 93   7.Sri Lanka - 90   8.West Indies - 75   9.Bangladesh - 74   10.Zimbabwe - 0  To read full article: http://v.duta.us/h6D6tQAA  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917397694031*  Type ðŸ‘VZ4 to like this  Type 'stop' to stop
*Lyon, Warner power series-saving Australia victory*  Australia 377 (Warner 123, Handscomb 82, Smith 58, Mustafizur 4-84) and 87 for 3 (Maxwell 25*) beat Bangladesh 305 (Mushfiqur 68, Sabbir 66, Lyon 7-94) and 157 (Lyon 6-60) by 7 wickets  History beckoned for Bangladesh this week, but it was the indefatigable Nathan Lyon who chose Chittagong to make plenty of his own and thus earn Australia a share of the series on a dramatic fourth day. Asian Test matches often move slowly before reaching a quick conclusion, and the visitors showed how much their knowledge of the game in this part of the world has grown by seizing the moment to pressure Bangladesh and emerge victorious with no little flourish.  Peter Handscomb and Glenn Maxwell took charge of a small target in fading light, after Lyon had made the sprint finish possible by scooping his third six-wicket haul in succession and scooping up a hatful of records in the process. Not least of these was the best haul by an Australian bowler in a two match series, a terrific 22 wickets, surpassing spin luminaries such as Shane Warne and Stuart MacGill. *Full MoU agreed as CA eyes T20 focus*  Australian cricket's pay war has formally ended with the completion of the full MoU between Cricket Australia and the Australian Cricketers Association for the next five years.  Negotiation and drafting of the full agreement took around two months, after a heads of agreement between the two warring parties was announced by the chief executives James Sutherland and Alistair Nicholson at the MCG on August 3. It is the first of its kind to include both women and men.  After 20 years of collective bargaining agreements adapted and expanded from the original revenue sharing deal struck in 1998, the new MoU has been largely simplified and more smoothly codified when compared to the labyrinthine deal reached in 2012. *Varun Aaron included in India Green squad for Duleep Trophy*  Jharkhand pacer Varun Aaron and Mumbai opener Prithvi Shaw have been included in India Green and India Red squads respectively for Duleep Trophy 2017. They were named as last-minute replacements after several players backed out due to number of issues.  From India Green, Mumbai batsman Shreyas Iyer and Jammu & Kashmir all-rounder Parvez Rasool have opted out of the tournament. While Iyer is nursing an injured knee, Rasool is reportedly expected to leave for Haj. India Red, on the other hand, sees three exclusions from the original squad. While Tamil Nadu skipper Abhinav Mukund is down with dengue, Dhawal Kulkarni and Ambati Rayudu also won't be available for the tournament. *Recovering Starc eyeing domestic run to boost Ashes preparations*  Australia paceman Mitchell Starc, who has been out of action since the Champions Trophy in June, is now looking forward to playing a few domestic games with an eye on the Ashes in November. The left-armer has spent the last few months in recovery, after scans revealed that he hadn't fully healed after fracturing his right foot on the tour of India in March.  The 27-year-old is now back to bowling, and is keen to don the New South Wales colours again for the One-Day Cup which commences in the final week of the month. Following that, Starc plans to play a couple of Shield games as well.  "It's nice to be back bowling," Starc said on Thursday (September 7). "It's been fantastic to be back with the Blues boys and training around the guys I haven't always had the chance to the last couple of years."  "Barring any hiccups I'll be taking part in the JLT Cup and hopefully those first couple of Shield games as well. I think that's a great lead-up for all the guys who are around the Test set-up, the guys who are looking to try and get in that team and some of us coming back from injury. It's first-class cricket hopefully on some Test venues. It's probably a better lead-in than most of the last few summers where we've had one Shield game, two at tops". *Cricket CSA congratulates Erasmus on umpiring 'ton'*  Cricket South Africa (CSA) has congratulated Marais Erasmus on becoming the second South African to stand as an on-field umpire in 100 first-class matches when he officiated in the third Test match between England and the West Indies at Lord's.  This is also Erasmus' 45th Test match.  "Congratulations once again to Marais as he achieves another landmark in his stellar career," commented CSA Chief Executive, Haroon Lorgat. ðŸ“° *EO2*: *Amir likely to miss World XI series*  Mohammad Amir's wait to play an international match in Pakistan will be prolonged, as he is likely to miss part, if not all, of the T20I series against the World XI. ðŸ“° *HC7*: *Playing Cricket in Pakistan: Not A Problem for Zimbabwe Captain*  Zimbabwe's Elton Chigumbura was the last international captain who visited Pakistan post 2009 terror attacks.   Though no player from his country is a playing member of the World XI team against Pakistan this week except Andy Flower who is a coach, Chigumbura will be following the matches with interest. He said: "I just love watching other teams play and will follow the proceedings in Pakistan. I have been there twice both trips were good. People there love their cricket and I enjoyed it."   Zimbabwe were the first team to play in Pakistan after the Sri Lankan bus was attacked by terrorists in Lahore, but the African players had no issues in 2015.   "Pakistan was safe, the security was good and they did a good job," Chigumbura remarked. Pakistan won the three-match series 2-0 with the final rain-marred ODI ending in a no-result. All their matches were held in Lahore. *ðŸš¨ UPDATE: Apple ðŸŽ devices announced ðŸ”Š with special anniversary ðŸŽŠ additionâ€¼ï¸*  *Apple Watch Series 3 *  The latest generation of the Apple Watch 3 has a mobile connection so it can send and receive messages, browse the internet and play songs from Apple Music without needing to be linked to an iPhone. It also works with Siri and has a 50 per cent better battery life.   The device, which is the same size and shape as the current Watch 2, can also make phone calls independently.   The Apple Watch 3 will be available on EE in the UK, with pre-orders opening on September 15. Apple Watch will start at $399 in the US for the cellular version and $349 for the non-cellular.   It has a battery life of up to 18 hours, a 70 per cent faster processor, GPS connection and is swimproof. The device is available in gold, silver, space grey, with new sports bands, and a new ceramic grey version.   The original Apple Watch is still available to buy at a new price of $249.   *Apple TV 4K*  Apple's smart TV box is now available in high quality. Films in 4K quality will be available on iTunes for the same price as HD movies and will upgrade current purchases to 4K HDR for no extra price. Amazon originals will also be available in the upgraded quality.   Later it will have live sports as well. There will notifications before games and during. Live news will also be a part of the TV app. All notifications can always be turned off.   *iPhone 8 and 8 plus*  "This is a huge step forward for iPhone," says Cook.   The iPhone 8 and 8 Plus has an all-glass body and comes in silver, space grey and a new gold colour. For those worried about cracking the front and back of the new device, Phil Schiller says the glass is reinforced with a steel and copper structure and is "the most durable ever in a smartphone".  The devices have 4.7-inch and 5.5-inch retina displays and run on an A11 bionic chip. The iPhone 8 has a 12MP rear facing camera that is more powerful and can take in 80 per cent more light than the iPhone 7. The iPhone 8 Plus comes with a dual-lens 12MP camera with similar upgrades.   The new phones can now charge wirelessly by being placed on an inductive surface. It works with the Qi wireless standard, which Apple says it will help expand to public spaces such as airports and cafes.   It will work with third party wireless chargers such as those from Mophie and Belkin. Apple didn't announce its own wireless charger, meaning owners will probably have to buy the accessory separately.  The iPhone 8 comes in 64 GB and 256 GB and starts at $699. The 8 plus comes in the same variants and starts at $799. The devices will be available for order from September 15 and in stores from September 22. iOS 11 will be available from September 19.   *iPhone 10:*  Apple announced the iPhone X at its event on Tuesday. The phone is pronounced "iPhone 10."  The iPhone X is Apple's most high-end iPhone of the year. It offers a complete redesign from the current iPhone 7 and iPhone 7 Plus and was introduced along with iPhone 8 and 8 plus.   It features a new OLED display that's more colorful than the LCD screens Apple used in earlier iPhones. Apple is branding it the "Super Retina Display." The screen runs almost top to bottom and side to side, too, something Apple has never done before.  Apple said OLED displays come with trade-offs compared to its Retina Displays, but that its Super Retina Display supports HDR, offers the best color accuracy on the market and 3D Touch support.  There's no more home button. You swipe up from the bottom of the screen to return home. That gesture also allows a user to multitask - swipe up and pause, and you can multitask and switch between apps. Users can call up Siri by saying "Hey Siri" or by pressing the side button.  iOS 11 will feature, among other things, peer-to-peer Apple Pay and a redesigned Control Centre. The phone also comes equipped with wireless charging.   The iPhone X will be available in space gray and silver. FaceID is used to unlock the device, authenticate Apple Pay and create customisable animated emoji, called animoji (there are 12 new animojis to create personal messages). The 3D front-facing camera learns what users look like and is only inaccurate one in 1 million times. It will come in 64GB and 256GB with prices starting from $999. It will ship from November 3.  *To follow Tech and Gadget News on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917550034820*  Type ðŸ‘IZ2 to like this

ðŸ“° *JG9*: *WhatsApp ðŸ“ž testing ability to recall ðŸ‘ˆðŸ¼ messages âœ‰ï¸, even deletes ðŸ˜® them from Android notifications*  If you've ever sent a WhatsApp reply to the wrong thread, sharing your pet-name for your partner with a business colleague, or you've engaged in a spot of drunk-messaging, it looks like you'll soon have the opportunity to recall the message either before or after it is read.  WABetaInfo, an unofficial Twitter channel devoted to news of WhatsApp betas, spotted the feature. WhatsApp is finally testing the Delete for Everyone feature: the server finally works, and it successfully recalls the message.  Also, if the server works this does not mean that the feature is currently enabled.  In a couple of subsequent tweets, it was noted that it also removed the message from notifications on both Android and iOS devices.  The last feature it tested, picture-in-picture for video calls, was spotted testing in late July and was made available to all Android 8.0 users earlier this month. *BomberðŸ’£ Kills 3âƒ£ Outside AfghanðŸ‡¦ðŸ‡« Cricket Stadium*  A suicide bomber struck outside a cricket stadium during a match in Afghanistan's capital Wednesday, killing at least three people and wounding seven others, officials said.  Kabul police spokesman Basir Mujahid said hundreds of people were inside watching a match when the bomber struck outside the gates where security guards were searching people.  Health Ministry official Mohammad Salim Rasouli confirmed the death toll, saying at least seven other people were wounded.  No one claimed responsibility for the attack.  The stadium was packed with people watching the Shpageeza Cricket League 2017, Afghanistan's annual domestic T20 Tournament.  The Tournament, which features six teams, started on Sep. 11 and runs through Sept. 22. All the teams have foreign players, mainly from Sri Lanka, Zimbabwe and South Africa.  The match was on a break while the attack happened, but resumed without delay. ðŸ“° *LY8*: *Mohammed Shami Working On New Plans For Steve Smith, David Warner*  Mohammed Shami has been recalled to the India side for the first three ODIs against Australia and is ready with all his plans in place for the visiting side. The Indian speedster has chalked up some strategy which he wants to effectively implement against top Australians like rival skipper Steve Smith and senior batsman David Warner.      "We have some plans for each of their batsmen -- (especially Smith and Warner). There's always some new plan in place. The key is about executing it on the field," Shami told reporters at the Eden Gardens on the sidelines of the Bengal Ranji team's training session.      India will take on Australia in the first ODI of the five-match series on September 17 at MA Chidambaram Stadium in Chennai. ðŸ“° *EW1*: *Steve Smith's Captaincy Is Challenged Now, Says Michael Clarke*  Michael Clarke, ahead of the second One-day International (ODI) between India and Australia, said that Steve Smith needs to define the way for his team in order to have success as his captaincy is challenged now.  "Smith's batting has been outstanding for a long time but his captaincy is challenged now. He needs to define the way for his team to have success," Clarke said. "It's high time that Australia make a comeback. I think this is the match that will decide the course of the series," he said of the Eden second one-dayer on September 21.  The former Australian captain also praised India's rookie spinner Kuldeep Yadav. "He is an attacking bowler. His control as a wrist spinner from the back of his hand is amazing as is his strength. He has got all the skills, spins both ways, bowls long spells. He did well in the Test series, " said the Pup. *China ðŸ‡¨ðŸ‡³ blocks ðŸš« Whatsappâ€¼ï¸*  China has largely blocked the WhatsApp messaging app, the latest move by Beijing to step up surveillance ahead of a big Communist Party gathering next month.  The disabling in mainland China of the Facebook-owned app is a setback for the social media giant, whose chief executive, Mark Zuckerberg, has been pushing to re-enter the Chinese market, and has been studying the Chinese language intensively. WhatsApp was the last of Facebook products to still be available in mainland China; the companyâ€™s main social media service has been blocked in China since 2009, and its Instagram image-sharing app is also unavailable.  In mid-July, Chinese censors began blocking video chats and the sending of photographs and other files using WhatsApp, and they stopped many voice chats, as well. But most text messages on the app continued to go through normally. The restrictions on video, audio chats and file sharing were at least temporarily lifted after a few weeks.  WhatsApp now appears to have been broadly disrupted in China, even for text messages, Nadim Kobeissi, an applied cryptographer at Symbolic Software, a Paris-based research start-up, said on Monday. The blocking of WhatsApp text messages suggests that Chinaâ€™s censors may have developed specialized software to interfere with such messages, which rely on an encryption technology that is used by few services other than WhatsApp, he said. ðŸ“° *HH3*: *ICC New RulesðŸ“œ: Official from Sep 28ðŸ“†*  The ICC has introduced a number of changes to its playing conditions which will be effective in all series starting 28 September or later.  *DRS Changes* ðŸ‘‡   ðŸ”° Umpire's Call Redemption: If an umpire's LBW decision is upheld: during DRS, but any one of the 3 conditions (impact, pitching in line & hitting the stumps) is labelled 'umpire's call' then the team is allowed to retain the review even though the decision is upheldðŸ‘.   ðŸ”°No Review Revival: A team is allowed only 2âƒ£ reviews in a Test innings. There won't be any top up after 80 oversðŸ˜¯.   ðŸ”°More Power to the TVðŸ“º umpire: If a batsman reviews an LBW decision and replays suggest that the ball strikes the pad and the bat simultaneously, then the 3rd umpire can overturnðŸ‘Ž the decision. Previously, the 3rd umpire would go with the on-field umpire's call.   ðŸ”°T20 Debut: DRS to be introduced in the shortest format as wellðŸ‘.  *And That's a Penalty* ðŸ‘‡   ðŸ”°After the ball is played back to a bowler if he flings the ball back in the direction of the batsman while he is still in the crease, then the batting team will be awarded 5 bonus runs if the throw strikes the batsman's arm as he takes evasive action.   ðŸ”°Red Card: A player can be sent offðŸ“• for a Level 4 offence which include threatening to assault an umpire, making deliberate or inappropriate contact with an umpire and physically assaulting another player.   ðŸ”°No more 2nd warning for bowlers who bowl beamers. One warning and if they err again they are suspended from bowling in that innings.  *Other Changes* ðŸ‘‡   ðŸ”°Bowlers' RespiteðŸ˜“: Bat's thickness cannot exceed 67mm   ðŸ”°Batsmen Bail Out: Once a batter has landed the bat behind the crease, he/she will not be ruled run-out/stumped even if the bails are dislodged when the bat bounces later.   ðŸ”°Rebound Rejoice: The helmet is now considered as part of fielder's person. So if a catch is completed after it rebounds of a fielder's helmet, the batsman is out.  *Technicalities* ðŸ‘‡   ðŸ”°Any byes or leg byes scored off a no-ball will now be scored separately. If a bye is run off a no-ball it will be treated as 1 bye+1 no ball. Previously it was called 2 no-balls.   ðŸ”°If the ball slips from the bowler's hand and bounces twice before reaching the batsman, it would be called a no-ball instead of a dead ball.   ðŸ”°Any cloth that the fielding side use to dry a ball needs to be approved by the umpires.   ðŸ”°A team is allowed to field a substitute keeper.     .  *To follow Cricket on Duta:* *Add to your group: +917550053527*  Type ðŸ‘HH3 to like this

ðŸ“° *JL4*: *Jarvis to return to Zimbabwe to resume international career*  Close on the heels of Brendan Taylor's return, Zimbabwe will now be boosted by the presence of Kyle Jarvis, who is set to end his County contract with Lancashire.  Jarvis's contract with Lancashire was due to expire at the end of the next season but the club granted him permission to be released early in order to pursure his international career. Itâ€™s not a perfectly edge-to-edge look, but there are just the trimmest of bezels at the top and bottom of the screen.  The smaller Pixel is sticking with a 5-inch display, squared-off corners, and thick bezels. The difference is on the back, where on both new phones the glass accent at the top has been shrunken down, so that it no longer encases the fingerprint sensor. The Pixelâ€™s camera lens has gotten larger and it now juts out from the back of the phone.  Both phones also support â€œActive Edge,â€ which means you can squeeze their sides to trigger certain actions. By default, itâ€™ll launch the Google Assistant and silence phone calls. JC2
ðŸ“° *JC2*: *The original Santa Claus found in Turkey?*  Children look away now! For Turkish archaeologists believe they have found the tomb of the original Santa Claus, otherwise known as Saint Nicholas. An intact tomb has been found underneath Saint Nicholas Church, in the Demre district of Turkey's south-west province of Antalya.  Demre was built on the ruins of Myra, where St Nicholas was thought to have lived in the 4th Century. Until now, the bones of St Nicholas were believed to be in Bari, Italy. It had been thought they were taken by Italian merchants in 1087 when Myra - at the time a Greek town - was invaded by the Seljuk Turks.  Cemil Karabayram, Antalya Director of Surveying and Monuments, said recent scientific and technological studies had revealed the existence of an intact tomb under the church. He also said that during a study of old documents they had found notes saying the bones taken to Bari had belonged to another priest.  A CT scan, a geo-radar and eight academics had been brought in for the final stages of the excavation work. "The world's eyes will be set on here. We claim that St Nicholas has been kept in this temple without any damage. We are at the last stage. If we get the results, Antalya's tourism will gain big momentum," he told the newspaper.
